<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Society Proposes Ban on Crackers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Amid reports of deaths and
injures by crackers on the eve of an Indian major festival, a
Delhi-based society has proposed ban on crackers in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Delhi Ophthalmology Society (DOS) said Thursday that it was
time to bring an effective legislation banning dangerous crackers
and to ensure these crackers do not fall into the hands of
children.
</P>
<P>
With Diwali, the festival of lights, approaching next Monday,
the number of patients queuing up at the hospital emergency
centers has increased in New Delhi and others parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that four children were burnt alive and six others
received serious burn injuries when a crackers shop caught fire in
a village in the north Uttar Pradesh Thursday.
</P>
<P>
DOS secretary Lalit Verma said that the 24-hour trauma center
at the All India Institute of Medical Science and other major
hospitals as well as private clinics were each receiving at least
seven to eight cases of children who had their eyes injured while
playing with bow and arrow and "missile" crackers.
</P>
<P>
There must be quality control for crackers which result in
burns and severe injuries to eyes during Divali every year, said
G. Mukherjee, president of the society.
</P>
<P>
The organization has issued a list of major do's and don'ts
asking people to burst crackers in open space only and wear cotton
clothes while doing so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
