<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Iceberg Breaks Away From Antarctica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- An iceberg, one and a half
times the size of Delaware and called A-38, snapped off
Antarctica's Ronne Ice Shelf this week and is floating free in the
sea, The Washington Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A-38, which is 92 miles long and 30 miles wide, has now moved a
couple of miles away from the parent ice mass since it cracked off
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Ice Center said the last huge iceberg called
B-9 broke off Antarctica in October 1987, and it was 96 miles
long.
</P>
<P>
The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, which
operates the NIC jointly with the Navy and Coast Guard, regards
the calving of icebergs as "a possible indicator of global
warming."
</P>
<P>
The Antarctic glaciers and ice sheets are the subject of
intensive on-side study by scientists from the United States and
other nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
