<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Remain Unchanged in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. consumer prices
index (CPI) remained unchanged in September thanks to falling
prices for gasoline, clothing and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted CPI stayed where it was after five
small increases from April through August, said the U.S. Labor
Department in a report released Friday.
</P>
<P>
This helped lower the inflation to merely 1.4 percent in the
first nine months of the year, better than the 11-year low of 1.7
percent for all of 1997, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The latest price report shows that inflation remains
substantial in some areas where the elderly incur disproportionate
expenses.
</P>
<P>
The cost of medical care jumped 0.3 percent in September and
was up at a 3.7 percent rate so far this year. But their benefits
from the social security will increase just 1.3 percent next year,
the smallest raise since 1987.
</P>
<P>
Prescription drug costs shot up 0.7 percent last month and have
risen at a 5.4 percent rate from January through September.
</P>
<P>
Energy prices in September fell 1.3 percent, pulled down by a 2
percent drop for gasoline and smaller declines for fuel oil,
electricity and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices have fallen at an 18.8 percent annual rate this
year. Though analysts do not expect a big increase any time soon
because of falling world demand for energy, they do not expect
prices to fall much more either.
</P>
<P>
Food prices were unchanged last month, but are up at a 2.1
percent rate year-to-date. In September, pork costs fell 1.4
percent, the largest drop in nine years. Fruit, vegetable and
coffee prices also fell.
</P>
<P>
In September, tobacco prices jumped 3.3 percent. They're up at
a 16.8 percent annual rate as tobacco companies seek to recoup the
cost of multimillion-dollar liability lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
Clothing costs, heavily influenced by the increasing
availability of inexpensive imports from Asia, fell 0.7 percent,
the largest decline in 19 months.
</P>
<P>
Computer prices in September fell 3.7 percent. Airline fares
slipped 0.9 percent, but are still 4 percent higher than a year
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
