<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India Conclude First Day of Talks  By Yang Shilong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani and Indian Foreign
Secretaries concluded their first day of talks with a rather
optimistic note here on Friday and the two sides agreed to "review
existing confidence building measures in order to enhance their
efficacy."
</P>
<P>
"They explored a full range of peace and security issues
including Confidence Building Measures and identified areas of
convergence," Pakistani Foreign Office spokesman Tariq Altaf told
reporters at a briefing at the end of the first session.
</P>
<P>
The talks covering issues of peace and security were held in a
"frank and cordial" manner, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the two foreign secretaries "agreed to
review existing confidence building measures in order to enhance
their efficacy" and they also explored ways and means to continue
discussion.
</P>
<P>
"The discussion will continue at the technical expert level on
Saturday," he said, adding a joint statement would be issued at
the end of talks on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We should not be expected to produce results after every
session," Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad said as he
emerged from the opening session of the talks with his Indian
counterpart K. Ragunath.
</P>
<P>
"We can come up with something categorical at the end of the
talks on Sunday," Shamshad said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Foreign Secretary did not make any comment except
that "I endorse the remarks of my (Pakistani) counterpart."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, before entering into the talks, Shamshad expressed
optimism about the dialogue process but said "no quick-fix"
solutions should be expected as it is the initiation of the
process.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, he said, are dealing with "very complex issues
and one has to be patient and no quick fix solutions" should be
expected from a few hours meeting.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary reiterated that the new challenges for
both Islamabad and New Delhi are to avoid an arms race in nuclear
and ballistic fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
