<HEADLINE> Russia Urges NATO to Drop Decision on Force Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia Friday urged NATO to drop
its "erroneous and regrettable" decision on military action
against Yugoslavia over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Chizhov, head of the Russian Foreign Ministry's Europe
III Department, said that if NATO does not abolish its decision in
favor of military action, it may complicate the formation of a
mission of observers of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Russia's part in the monitoring operation may only be
discussed after NATO has canceled its decision on military
intervention," the Interfax news agency quoted Chizhov as saying.
</P>
<P>
"From the very beginning Russia has categorically opposed using
force to settle the Kosovo problem," Chizhov said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the NATO Council announced its political consent to
the use of force against Belgrade with a 96-hour delay of military
actions.
</P>
<P>
The ultimatum expires on Saturday, October 17.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question on Moscow's position if NATO troops
are sent to Kosovo to protect OSCE civil observers in the area, he
said, "There has been and there will be no talk about deploying
any foreign troops on the territory of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
Russia will be part of the leadership of the OSCE mission and
will fund a portion of its budget, Chizhov said.
</P>
<P>
"It makes more sense to pay for peace than for war," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
