<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Hold Military Exercises Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus announced Friday that
the armed forces will hold the annual exercises code-named
"Nikiforos '98" next week in conjunction with the war games
code-named "Toxotis" conducted by the Greek Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
National Guard General Command officer Panayiotis Tatsiopoulos
told a press conference that the six-day joint exercises will take
place according to a joint defense pact between Cyprus and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact signed in 1993, Greece will provide military
assistance to Cyprus in case the Mediterranean island is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Tatsiopoulos said the exercises and a search and rescue
operation off the western coast are aimed at assessing the
competence of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Advanced T80 and BMB3 tanks and parachutists will take part in
the maneuvers joined by the Greek naval and air forces, he said.
</P>
<P>
The major part of the exercises will take place in the
southeastern district of Larnaca with the use of live ammunition,
the officer said, adding that Greek warplanes may land at the
"Andreas Papandreou" air base near the southwestern town of Paphos.
</P>
<P>
Last year, after participation of Greek naval and air forces in
an identical annual exercise in Cyprus, Turkey sent military
aircraft and warships to the Turkish Cypriot-controlled northern
part of the island for retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed pro-Athens coup by the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus to protect
the Turkish Cypriots, who declared unilaterally in 1983 a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by
Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
