<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-16 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Rejects Syria's Offer for Wide-range Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Friday rejected an
offer from Syria for wide-range talks with Turkey, saying what
concerns Ankara now is only the issue of Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment Turkey wants to see whether Syria has put an
end to her support to terrorism," a written statement issued by
the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Syria said that it was waiting for Turkey's reply for
the reconvention of the Syrian-Turkish joint committee, a
mechanism set up in 1992 to solve a wide range of issues between
the two countries, including the dispute of sharing water
resources from the Euphrates.
</P>
<P>
"The only issue on Turkey's agenda is support given to the
Kurdish rebels," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of backing Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), but Damascus has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said that
Turkey would take decisive measures if Syria continues supporting
the PKK which has been fighting for autonomy in southeast Turkey
since 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
