<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Opposes Release of EU Funds to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Greece Friday expressed its
opposition to the release of European Union (EU) funds to
neighboring Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reports that European Foreign Affairs
Commissioner Hans Van Den Broek was considering releasing EU funds
to Turkey through some different channel, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said that any attempt to release EU
funds to Turkey by a different path would be "legally groundless
and politically unorthodox."
</P>
<P>
He warned that apart from the veto exercised by Greece on the
release of EU funds allocated to Turkey under the 4th financial
protocol, Greece could also have recourse to the European court.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at odds for
decades over their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits, the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Athens has insisted that it will not lift its veto on the
release of EU funds to the neighboring country unless Ankara
improves it human rights record and relations with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
