<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Lauds Nobel Peace Prize Winners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Friday "warmly congratulates" the co-winners of the
1998 Nobel Peace Prize, John Hume and David Trimble, saying the
award "is a tribute to their personal courage and leadership and
their contribution to putting Northern Ireland onto the path of
peace."
</P>
<P>
The remarks were contained in the U.N. chief's statement issued
through his spokesman's office here. Annan, in the statement,
praised the two winners' efforts to facilitate the signing of the
landmark Northern Ireland Peace Agreement last April.
</P>
<P>
Annan wishes the co-recipients of the 1998 award every success
as they continue to work for peace in Northern Island, the
statement said, adding that he hopes that the award will also
encourage those who may still have reservations about the peace
agreement which the two winners have worked so hard to achieve to
now lend their unremitting support to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Annan paid a one-day visit Friday to Washington, where he is
scheduled to address the Empower America Fall Conference and the
World Press Freedom Committee. He will return to New York late
Friday, the U.N. spokesman, Hiro Ueki, said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
