<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Extends Air Strike Ultimatum Till Oct. 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- NATO extended Friday its
ultimatum for air strikes in Kosovo to October 27, a senior NATO
official said.
</P>
<P>
NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told the press that the North
Atlantic Council, the decision-making body of the 16-nation
Western military alliance, Friday decided to maintain NATO's
readiness to launch air operations against Yugoslavia, including
the deployment of substantial air forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
But the council decided that the period before execution of air
strikes will be extended until October 27, or for 10 more days.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the council will monitor developments
in Kosovo closely.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, the North Atlantic Council urged
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to take urgent steps to
ensure that full compliance is achieved in this time period.
</P>
<P>
Shea said that the allies have found clear evidence that there
is still some distance from full compliance on the ground. Many
army and special units, that normally based outside Kosovo, are
still deployed in Kosovo, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The ultimatum was originally set for Saturday for full and
verifiable compliance by Belgrade with United Nations Security
Council Resolution 1199.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana went to
Belgrade to sign an air-borne surveillance agreement with
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Yugoslavia agreed to set up a liaison mechanism for
the implementation of the air surveillance that will use unarmed
NATO airplanes.
</P>
<P>
The agreement required Yugoslavia to shut off radars that would
otherwise illuminate or lock down surveillance planes.
</P>
<P>
NATO warned that Yugoslavia will have to bear "grave
consequences" should it choose to breach the agreement and use its
radars against surveillance planes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota Takes 40 Percent of Zambia's Motor Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Toyota, one of Japan's big
automakers, have covered 40 percent of the Zambian market,
according the managing director of the Toyota Zambia Ltd..
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon hosted Friday in Lusaka by the company which
deals in Toyota cars in Zambia, Martin Grasett told Xinhua that
his company's marketing performance has been outstanding in the
past years, with at least 800 vehicles sold each year in the
local market.
</P>
<P>
The company, which came to Zambia in 1963 before the country
won its independence, has embarked on an expansion program worth
1.4 million U.S. Dollars to its existing premises in a bid to
provide more convenience for its potential customers.
</P>
<P>
The luncheon was held to officially mark the commencement of
the building project.
</P>
<P>
The 48-week long project will see additions of a new vehicle
show room, new parts outlet and Toyoshop and the latest customer
care facilities, said the managing director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
