<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: United Actions Called for in Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Chen Cailin
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- October 17 will mark the
International Day for the Eradication of Poverty, a day which was
set aside by the United Nations to galvanize support both at the
national and global levels for eradicating poverty.
</P>
<P>
It is well known that significant gains have been achieved in
economic growth and living standards worldwide over the past
three decades. However, there are over 1.3 billion people around
the world, almost one-third of humanity, who still live under
extreme poverty with less one U.S. Dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
Despite a dramatic surge in global consumption, with real
expenditures doubling over the past 25 years, more than one
billion people can not still meet their most basic needs, a 1998
U.N. report said.
</P>
<P>
These people lack especially the access to the fundamentals of
a decent life, such as sufficient food, safe water, reliable
health care, adequate shelter, basic education and opportunities
to sustain livelihoods and to participate in decisions that
affect their livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
Among the 4.4 billion people who live in developing countries,
almost three-fifths live in communities without basic sanitation
facilities; almost one-third are without safe drinking water; one
quarter lack adequate housing; one-fifth live beyond the reach of
modern health services; and one-fifth of the children are
undernourished, figures released by U.N. agencies said.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan Africa bears the brunt of poverty. It is not only
the region with the highest incidence of poverty in the world,
with over 40 percent of its inhabitants living below the one
Dollar a day poverty line.
</P>
<P>
More and more countries are trying to develop anti-poverty
strategies. At the World Summit for Social Development in
Copenhagen, Denmark in March, 1995, Heads of State and senior
officials from over 180 countries acknowledged the worsening
problem of global poverty and pledged to take actions to combat
poverty.
</P>
<P>
The delegates to the summit agreed to develop national
anti-poverty strategies to eliminate the worst aspects of poverty
in their countries on a time bound basis. The U.N. system, on its
part, was mandated to assist the member countries towards the
realization of such a goal and thus the International Decade for
the Eradication of Poverty was established.
</P>
<P>
To eradicate poverty, it is firstly needed to stop and control
armed conflicts and civil strife in many developing countries
where almost 100 million people are caught in a cycle of civil
strife and hunger. Armed conflicts handicap especially the African
economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
According to the report by U.N. chief Kofi Annan, on April 16,
this year, 14 of the 53 African countries were afflicted by armed
conflict in 1996, and over 30 wars have been occurred since 1970,
mostly within states.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, international community, especially the developed world,
has the responsibility to help the highly-indebted poor countries
to reduce their debt burden and increase development assistance
to the poor.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in the report that Africa's debt burden remain
unsustainable, noting that Africa paid 33 billion Dollars in debt
repayment in 1997, eight billion dollars more than it paid in
1995.
</P>
<P>
It should be noted that the international community has made
and is making efforts to help the poor to combat poverty.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has repeated its calls for partnerships between
governments, the donor community, civil society, non-governmental
organizations, and the poor themselves in the fight for building
a world without poverty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Week Launched in Addis Ababa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- This Year's United Nations
Week was launched Friday in Addis Ababa, Capital of Ethiopia, by
U.N. Resident Coordinator Sam Nyambi.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held at the U.N. Conference Center here,
Nyambi said October 17, 1998 marks the International Day for the
Eradication of Poverty, and the U.N. public forum on poverty
eradication in Ethiopia will be held at Africa Hall here on the
same day.
</P>
<P>
Nyambi said Africa is highest incidence of poverty in the
world, with over 40 percent of its inhabitants living below the
one U.S. Dollar a day poverty line.
</P>
<P>
There are 18 U.N. agencies in Addis Ababa whose activities
are centered in development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nyambi announced the launching of an essay
contest in primary, secondary, technical and vocational schools
on the theme "imagine and describe how to build a world without
poverty".
</P>
<P>
According to Nyambi, during the U.N. Week, activities such as
national human development report workshop, U.N. model assembly
and pledging of computers to schools, disabled sports show and
U.N. flag raising will be held in Addis Ababa.  
</P>
