<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian FM Urges Speedy Ratification of START II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov Friday urged the State Duma, or lower house of parliament,
to ratify the START II arms reduction treaties as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting in St. Petersburg commemorating Alexander
Gorchakov, a Russian career diplomat in the 19th century, Ivanov
said a speedy ratification of the treaty corresponds with Russia's
national interests.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, it is also important that the United States ratify
all documents pertaining to the treaty," the Interfax quoted
Ivanov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov's speech covered a wide range of topics on Russian
foreign policy, from Kosovo to arms reduction to cooperation among
members of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
"Russia's foreign policy today aims to resolve two tasks
simultaneously: to ensure the most favorable external conditions
for domestic reforms and to prevent Russia's positions in the
international arena from weakening," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
This may be achieved only by implementing an energetic,
multifaceted foreign policy like the one Russia is pursuing now,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Our strategic course is clear: to create a multifaceted and
democratic world and closely cooperate with other countries for
resolving world problems only by peaceful means," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Kosovo, Ivanov said possible political and military
scenarios are being developed in the Balkans which may
predetermine further development of the international process.
</P>
<P>
"Resolution of Balkan problems and primarily the Kosovo issue
is one of the most complicated tasks for international and
European policy-makers."
</P>
<P>
"Russia is firmly and definitively insisting on a political
solution to the Kosovo problem," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
The potential of constructive energetic diplomacy is far
greater than that of military force, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov also called for comprehensive efforts to ensure the
nonproliferation of weapons of mass destruction and means for
their delivery should be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
"Russia, as a depository of the Treaty on the Nonproliferation
of Nuclear Weapons, is trying to make it universal," Ivanov said.
"We also support having all countries join the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty."
</P>
<P>
"Russia is ready to continue its resolute movement towards
further reduction of its nuclear arsenals and maintenance of
strategic stability at lower military levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
On European security and cooperation in the next century,
Ivanov said the new system should ensure the security of all
countries on the continent "without exception."
</P>
<P>
"This should be the underlying principle of the European
Security Charter that is being prepared by the OSCE (Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe)," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The new Europe cannot be based on any sort of NATO-centered
models," Ivanov stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
