<HEADLINE> Palestine-Israel Summit Enters Second Day in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators Friday started a second day of tough talks in Wye
Mills, Maryland, aimed at breaking the 19-month impasse in the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The delegations broke up into groups specializing in security,
economic issues, the Palestinian airport in Gaza and setting up of
a safe passage for Palestinians between Gaza and the West Bank,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to close a deal on Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank, coupled with Palestinian security measures to protect
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The central issue is a U.S. proposal for Israel to pull back
troops from a further 13 percent of the West Bank in exchange for
specific Palestinian assurances to crack down on militants and
give cast-iron security commitments.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who is overseeing
the talks, is expected to hold a three-way meeting later in the
day with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
"There is hard work ahead if we are to reach an agreement....
Our entire team (is) ready to do whatever we can. We are ready to
get to work," Clinton told the opening session.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met the two leaders at the White House before he
formally opened the summit in Wye River Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
In a Rose Garden statement following the White House meeting,
Clinton urged the two leaders to "break the logjam" in the peace
process. "Too much time has already been lost," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As in any difficult problem, neither side can expect to win
100 percent of every point," he said. "But concessions that seem
hard now will seem far less important in the light of an accord
that moves Israelis and Palestinians closer to lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
Thursday afternoon, Clinton had five meetings with Netanyahu
and Arafat, either separately or together, and committees worked
late into the evening, Palestinian spokesman Marwan Kanafani said.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders shared dinner before Clinton headed home to
Washington around midnight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
