<HEADLINE> Yemen, Eritrea to Set up Joint Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- In a sign to enhance the newly
improved relations, Yemen and Eritrea signed an agreement Friday
in Asmara to set up a joint committee, the Yemeni News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Yemeni Foreign Minister Abdul
Qader Ba-Jammal and Eritrean Trade and Industry Minister Ali
Sayed, the news agency said. Ba-Jammal started his visit to
Eritrea Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed committee will cover all the areas of common
interest, probing programs on expanding bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ad hoc committees will be formed to carry out specific tasks
and raise recommendations to the joint committee for approval.
</P>
<P>
The agreement encourages exchange of visits and meetings of
officials between the two sides, and exchange of information and
documents related to the cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It calls for continued contacts between the two sides to work
out the agendas of the joint committee.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, the Yemeni foreign minister said
the agreement turns over a new page of the bilateral relations and
usher in a new era, which will see political and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Yemen and Eritrea have recently ended disputes over sovereignty
of the Hanish archipelago in the Red Sea through international
arbitration, which ruled that the island belongs to Yemen.
</P>
</TEXT>
