<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Cease-Fire Among Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations Friday urged all Afghan warring parties to call
a cease-fire and begin negotiations leading to a broader-based
government in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the council reviewed the lastest report on
Afghanistan by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and was briefed
by U.N. Under-Secretary-General Kieran Prendergast about the
current mission of Special Envoy Lakhdar Brahimi to the region.
</P>
<P>
Member of the council welcomed the progress made by Special
Envoy Brahimi in his efforts based on Security Council relevant
resolutions to reduce tensions in the region and to improve the
human rights and humanitarian situation in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Members of the council reaffirmed their very strong support and
appreciation for Special Envoy Brahimi's continuing efforts to
secure the implementation of those resolutions, and the underlying
need for all parties to implement fully the commitments they had
already entered into.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed deep concern at the continuing fighting
and over the humanitarian and human rights situation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The council called on all parties to respect humanitarian law
and to observe human rights norms to grant full access to
international humanitarian organizations and to guarantee security
for U.N. and other international personnel.
</P>
<P>
The council also expressed its concern at the continuing use of
Taleban-controlled territory for the cultivation of drugs and for
the sheltering and training of terrorists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
