<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Net Overseas Earnings for UK Soars To Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The financial services industry
earned a record 25.2 billion pounds (40.3 billion U.S. dollars)
from overseas work, loans and investment in 1997, according to new
figures out Friday.
</P>
<P>
Helped by last year's booming financial markets, the City's
contribution to the British economy has doubled in the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
About 14 billion pounds (22.4 billion dollars) of 1997's total
is made up of fee income for services, such as stockbroking or
banking, and the remainder is income, such as dividends, coming
from investments made abroad.
</P>
<P>
The earnings figures were compiled by British Invisibles (BI),
the private organization that promotes the UK financial services
industry internationally.
</P>
<P>
BI said the net overseas earnings of banks located in the UK
were 7.75 billion pounds (12.4 billion dollars), with insurance
institutions pulling in 7.42 billion pounds (11.87 billion
dollars). Pension funds recorded foreign earnings of 2.13 billion
pounds (3.4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figures underlines the City's position as the financial
capital of Europe and helps explain why London's economy is now
bigger than those of Denmark, Sweden and Austria.
</P>
<P>
The City, which is only one square mile, alone provides about
250,000 jobs. There are 550 foreign banks based in London, more
than any other city in the world.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the average daily turnover of London's foreign
exchange market was 637 billion pounds (1,019.2 billion dollars),
more than New York and Tokyo combined.
</P>
<P>
Duncan Mackenzie, BI's director of economics, said, "The City's
depth of expertise has a vital role to play in a wide range of
challenges from handling transactions in the euro to meeting the
needs of clients in both emerging and advanced economies alike."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
