<HEADLINE> Liberia Denies Deploying Troops at Border With S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government has
denied an allegation by Sierra Leone that Liberia had deployed
5,000 armed men at its border to attack the country, the News
Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday by the Liberian Foreign
Ministry, the government expressed disappointment over the
allegation, especially at the time when efforts are being made to
reawaken the spirit of cooperation under the Mano River Union, an
economic union between the two west African countries.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "the government of Liberia calls on
the U.N., ECOMOG (West African Peace-Keeping Force), the press
and other interested parties to send investigative teams to the
border to ascertain the truth of Khbbah's allegation."
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG said earlier on Thursday that fighters from Liberia
were helping rebels in neighboring Sierra Leone, adding that
"foreign fighters from Liberia" were assisting rebels of the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) in the south of the country.
</P>
<P>
The RUF, together with supporters of a junta which was
overthrown by ECOMOG from power in February, are blamed for a
terror campaign in southern part of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean government has complained about the
presence of the Liberian troops both to the Economic Community of
the West African States and to the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
</TEXT>
