<HEADLINE> Tanzania in Unfavorable Trade with Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian financial
minister has said that his country suffered an unfavorable trade
with its neighbor Kenya in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
While Tanzania is currently selling goods worth between seven
to ten billion Shillings to Kenya annually, it imports goods
worth 100 billion Shillings (about 149 million U.S. Dollars)
every year.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports Friday, the Minister of Finance
Daniel Yona said that Tanzania will maintain its tariffs for some
commodities to protect local industries such as sugar and tyre.
</P>
<P>
For example, a minimum duty of 399 U.S. Dollars per ton has
been set on imported sugar in an effort to protect the sugar
industries, Yona said to a delegation of the Kenyan Association
of Manufacturers (KAM) in Dar es Salaam Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan delegation which has been in Tanzania since last
Sunday are leaving this weekend after meeting business people
here. 
</P>
