<HEADLINE> Burundi Warring Factions Call for Transitional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Three warring Burundi
factions Friday called for an immediate establishment of a
transitional government to end ethnic civil war in the
land-locked African country.
</P>
<P>
Presenting views at the on-going third round of Burundi peace
talks in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha, the warring parties
said that the establishment of transitional body would pave way
for free and fair general elections and restore peace in the
war-torn tiny central African republic, according to meeting
sources.
</P>
<P>
The talks are brokered by former Tanzanian President, Julius
Nyerere, who also chaired the previous two rounds in Arusha in
June and July respectively.
</P>
<P>
"There must be a transitional government to allow peace to
settle in Burundi," the meeting sources quoted former president
of Burundi, Jean Baptise Bagaza, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Jean Minani, the president of pro-Hutu party Frodebu, also
supported the call at the talks for transitional organs alongside
with another rebel group, Palipehutu.
</P>
<P>
"We'll not overcome our problems if we don't have a government
which is reflective of different thoughts of people," Minani said
at the talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Council for Defense and Democracy (CNDD), the
largest rebel group in Burundi, suggested at the meeting that
about 10,000 Hutus imprisoned in the country should be set free
to allow the peace dialog to continue.
</P>
<P>
"The Hutus must be freed and given a fair treatment," said
Leon Ndarubagi, secretary of the rebel group fighting to topple
the government of President Pierre Buyoya who came to power in a
military coup in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The RPB party suggested for the establishment of a Burundi
tribunal which should try those who committed crimes of genocide,
similar to a court started by the United Nations for Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
On Friday afternoon, a women group from Burundi, which has
asked to be included in the talks, made its presentation to end
the country's ethnic war which has since 1993 killed more than
150,000 people, mostly civilians, in a series of massacres and in
armed conflict between the Tutsi-dominated army and the Hutu
rebels.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman for Nyerere, Brigadier-General
Hashim Mbita, the debate will continue on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Those who have so far spoken at the debate include Burundi's
National Assembly, Frolina, Inkinzo, PL, UPRONA, Palipehutu,
Frodebu, RPB, CNDD, Abassa and two former Burundi presidents --
Bagaza and Sylvestre Ntibantunganya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Congratulates 1998 Nobel Peace Winners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund Executive Director Carol Bellamy Friday congratulated the
1998 Nobel Peace Prize winners, John Hume and David Trimble, for
their contribution to the peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said in a statement, "Their perseverance diplomacy in
bringing two entrenched sides together after years of bitter
conflict is an example to all who presently seek solutions to
equally difficult conflicts throughout the world."
</P>
<P>
"It is important also to congratulate the Nobel Committee for
helping to focus world attention on the Colombia Children's
Movement for Peace, whose nomination was a recommendation of the
incredible potential of children as peace-makers in today's
world," the executive director said.
</P>
<P>
"The presence of the Children's Movement as a serious contender
among this year's Nobel nominees is a signal to all nations in
conflict," Bellamy said. "In many conflict situations where adults
have failed to make peace, it will take the growing involvement of
children and young people to turn the tide."
</P>
<P>
Bellamy said that Colombia's young peace-makers exemplify the
ideals of the Convention on the Rights of Child, the world's most
widely ratified human rights accord. "The convention stresses that
children should be brought up to affirm peace, dignity, tolerance,
freedom, equality and solidarity," Bellamy said. "The children of
Colombia, faced with intolerable violence, have done this in no
uncertain terms and achieved remarkable results."
</P>
<P>
UNICEF Colombia has been closedly involved with the Colombia
Children's Movement since its inception. In October 1996, the
Children's Movement for Peace helped mobilize children living in
the most violent municipalities of Colombia to vote in a special
election -- known as the Children's Mandate for Peace and Rights.
</P>
<P>
The children were asked to choose which of their rights were
most important to themselves and to their communities.
</P>
<P>
At first, it was thought no more than 300,000 children would
vote, but the movement grew so quickly that more than 2.7 million
children aged 7 to 18 years old turned up at the polls, about a
third of the age-group population nationwide. The turn-out in many
of the most violent municipalities was higher than 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
The children voted overwhelmingly in favor of the right to
survive and the right to peace. "The result sent shock-waves
through the nation," the UNICEF statement said.
</P>
<P>
A year later, more than 10 million adult Colombians (compared
with just more than 4 million who had voted in the previous 1994
presidential elections) turned out at the polls to support a peace
referendum that included backing for the Children's Mandate,
condemned the atrocities of the war and pledged their personal
commitment to help make peace.
</P>
<P>
As a result, peace became the main issue on which the 1998
presidential elections were fought and became the priority of the
new administration of Andres Pastranan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
