<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Virus May Mutate in Male's Genital and blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS virus can mutate
into different, drug-resistant strains in patient's semen and
blood, researchers from U.S. and Switzerland reported in the
latest issue of the AIDS journal.
</P>
<P>
The researchers studied 11 HIV-infected men in North Carolina
and Switzerland. Some of those who were treated prior to the study
had AIDS strains that had mutated and developed resistance to
antiviral drugs. Most of the volunteers with these resistant
viruses had different viral strains in their semen and blood.
</P>
<P>
They found that even the powerful AIDS drug protease inhibitors
did not penetrate the male genitals, or did so only with great
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
In one patient, they discovered, resistance to the drug AZT was
found in the sperm virus, and later in the blood virus.
</P>
<P>
Thus they concluded that the male genitals and the
bloodstream act as separate "compartments" that have to be dealt
with independently when giving AIDS drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Urged to Strengthen Check on Private Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. investigator on
the use of mercenaries on Friday recommended that the General
Assembly of the United Nations call for strengthened supervision
and scrutiny of private companies that provide military advice and
assistance on the international market.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Special Rapporteur of the United Nations Human
Rights Commission Enrigue Bernales Ballesteros said this should
apply even when such services had been agreed with legitimate or
constitutional governments or for the purpose of reinstating them.
</P>
<P>
The Special Rapporteur said since these companies usually hired
mercenaries to provide the military component of their services,
attention must be paid to the need to regulate and restrict their
operations to prevent them from interfering in internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
He recommended that the General Assembly authorize the conduct
of studies and the drafting of proposals for strengthening
international prevention, action and response mechanisms in all
cases where there was a serious threat to the enjoyment of human
rights, the exercise of the right to self-determination of
peoples, internal law and order, life and peace.
</P>
<P>
The Special Rapporteur said this applied particularly in
situations of internal armed conflict which could extend beyond
national boundaries or have regional repercussions.
</P>
<P>
"This would limit the activities of private security and
military assistance companies strictly to providing technical and
professional advisory services in accordance with the relevant
legal norms," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
