<HEADLINE> Three New Judges to be Selected for Hague Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd General
Assembly session on Friday voted to select three judges to fill a
new trial chamber of the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal, whose
caseload is expected to grow with atrocities allegedly committed
during the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the 185-member assembly case secret ballots
to choose among candidates nominated by their home countries. The
three will rule on cases concerning crimes committed in the former
Yugoslavia. Their terms will end on November 16, 2001.
</P>
<P>
David Anthony Hunt of Australia and Patrick Lipton Robinson
of Jamaica received more than 94 votes needed for a majority
after two rounds of balloting.
</P>
<P>
A third round failed to produce a selection. A fourth round was
scheduled to choose between the remaining candidates, Mohamed
Bennouna of Morocco and Peter H. Wilkitzki of Germany.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Ecuador, Finland, Sri Lanka and Chile withdrew their
candidates to make a final result easier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
