<HEADLINE> Kosovo Albanian Leader Supports Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The political
leader of the Ethnic Albanians in Kosovo Ibrahim Rugova said on
Friday he supports the OSCE mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with Bronislaw Geremek, chairman of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in the
Kosovo capital Pristina, Rugova said, "I can assure you that all
the people will support the OSCE mission."
</P>
<P>
He also said that "people in Kosovo want the international
presence for their protection," and he believed the Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA) would respect the OSCE mission as well.
</P>
<P>
Geremek arrived in Kosovo later in the day to win support of
all parties for the OSCE mission after signing the agreement
Friday morning in Belgrade with Yugoslav leaders.
</P>
<P>
Two thousand OSCE verification force will be deployed in Kosovo
to ensure that the U.N. resolution is complied with and all Serb
troops are withdrawn from Kosovo to allow refugees to return home
before winter comes.
</P>
<P>
Both Rugova and the separate Albanian guerrilla group KLA said
the agreement reached by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke on Tuesday was not acceptable as the
ethnic Albanians' demand was full independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nato announced that it gives Yugoslavia an
additional 10 days to comply with United Nations demands for a
peaceful resolution to the crisis in Kosovo. However, the Western
military alliance was not satisfied with the pace of withdrawal of
Serbian troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We are still far from seeing full compliance with what the
international community wants," Nato Secretary-General Javier
Solana said on Friday morning in Belgrade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
