<HEADLINE> COMESA to Implement Common External Tariff By </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) has reached an agreement to
implement a common external tariff by the year 2000, COMESA trade
advisor M.J. Musonda said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Musonda said COMESA is one of the most successful regional
economic cooperation and integration groups not only in Africa
but also the world over.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA trade advisor said that all COMESA countries are
committed to reducing tariffs at a symposium on "Ethiopia and
Enlarged COMESA Market by the Year 2000" held in the capital of
this east African country, Ethiopian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said, seven countries including Comoros, Eritrea, Kenya,
Mauritius, Sudan, Uganda and Zimbabwe have reached the 80 percent
reduction level as of September 1998 while four other countries
have reduced tariffs by 60 or 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
He noted that inter-COMESA trade grew from 834 million U.S.
Dollars in 1985 to 2.5 billion Dollars in 1996 as a result of
COMESA trade liberalization and facilitation programs, with
further potential growth of four billion Dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
Achievements in elimination of non-tariff barriers include
liberalization of import licensing, removal of foreign exchange
restrictions and taxes on foreign exchange, removal of import and
export quotas, removal of road blocks, and easing of customs
formalities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
