<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Economic Growth Slows Down: Document </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of Angola
said in a document Friday that Angola's economic growth has
slowed down evidently, with a predicted growth rate of only 1.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
In the document summarizing the performance of the national
economy in 1998, Angola's central bank pointed out that the
government's revenue will decrease because the petroleum industry
of the southern African country has been affected by the
faltering peace process and the lowering crude oil prices in the
international market.
</P>
<P>
It said that the growth of the petroleum sector and mining
sector will both slow down to 2.5 percent. The two sectors
account for 45 percent of Angola's gross domestic products (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the monetary policy for 1998, the national bank
said that it will keep committing itself to curbing the
inflation.
</P>
<P>
On account of the dropping crude prices in the international
market, the Angolan central bank has revised upward its inflation
target from the previous less than 30 percent to the current 75
percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the price for crude oil in the international market
remained around the level of 18.6 U.S. Dollars per barrel.
However, it has so far plunged to 12 Dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the bank said that it will further take direct and
indirect measures to control money supply. It will limit loans
directly by setting the maximum and minimum of interest rates,
while introducing the reserve system.
</P>
<P>
Angola's GDP grew by nearly six percent for 1997, with the
processing sector recording the fastest growth rate at 92
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
