<HEADLINE> Zambia Considers Reducing Excise Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
considering reducing excise duty on soft drinks, cigarettes and
clear beer, Zambian Minister of Commerce, Trade and Industry
David Mpamba said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mpamba told an annual general meeting of the Lusaka Chamber of
Commerce and Industry Association that other issues to be
considered include duty on some imported materials and levy on
the informal sector.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that the Zambian government is
considering the reestablishment of the tariff advisory board.
</P>
<P>
The government is aware of the concerns of the business
community about the generally weak situation in the economy, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Chairman for Lusaka Chamber, Gaudenzio Rossi, said on the same
occasion that the government should come up with economic
policies that will focus on Zambians to revitalize the economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
At the same meeting, Chairman for the Zambia Association of
Chambers of Commerce and Industry (ZACCI) George Chabwera called
on the government and business community to hold dialog in a bid
to enhance economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Cola-Cola company in Zambia recently urged the
government of the southern African country to honor its promise
made last May to reduce the excise duty to five percent from 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
Due to the Zambian government's inability to reduce the excise
duty, the Coca-Cola company, increased its price last month to
900 Kwacha (0.45 U.S. Dollar) from 500 Kwacha (0.25 Dollar) per
bottle.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the sharp price hike, the company's sale
dropped by 70 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
