<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End Week Sharply Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets posted
large gains at the end of the week, reinvigorated by an unexpected
rate cut of 0.25 percent by the U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
But early euphoria was later tempered by scepticism that the
European Central Bank and the Bundesbank would not follow suit.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 finished the week with a 6.4 percent rise
thanks to the rate-cut inspired rally on Wall Street for the
second day running and advances in Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 closed up 77 at 5133 in healthy turnover of 1.05bn
shares. The FTSE 250 jumped 94 to 4564.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate cuts in Hong Kong and Canada added to the
feel-good factor and fuelled hopes of another rate cut in the U.K,
although an inter-meeting easing by the Bank of England has
largely been ruled out by analysts.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the electronic Xetra Dax closed up 79 points at
4469, down slightly from an early morning high of 4578.
</P>
<P>
"Pretty clearly the U.S. interest rate cut is the reason for
the market rise," said a trader at the Hamburg-based MM Warburg.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the leading Cac 40 index had a more disappointing
turnout, ending 3390 by the end of the session after an initial
rise of 89 points to 3451.76.
</P>
<P>
"We recovered from September and early October losses... and
investors are pausing, looking for new elements that would justify
pushing the index higher," said a trader at a Paris-based
brokerage house.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks rallied as further reports in the French press
managed to ease investors' worries over banks' hidden exposure to
hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, Russia's stock market continued its gradual climb
from the deep freeze on Friday, bounding ahead almost 10 percent
in the first hour of trading in an abrupt about turn after months
of seemingly endless falls. But the rally faltered and the index
fell back by 3.6 percent when trading was halted at 12:30PM local
time.
</P>
<P>
But the RTS index was still up nearly 30 percent on the week as
investors were attracted by the bargain prices of Russia's blue
chip companies.
</P>
<P>
The leading RTS index which had lost 90 percent of its value
this year, was reached 64.57 at its high before ending the week at
56.62.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas companies proved particularly attractive, despite
the perils of investing in a country gripped by a devastating
economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
