<HEADLINE> S. Africa-EU Trade Talks Still in Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 16 (Xinhua) -- This week's trade talks
between South Africa and the European Union (EU) failed to
resolve an impasse over EU's tariff reduction offer for farm
products, a senior South African trade official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, the negotiations did not achieve sufficient progress
on the key issue of agriculture, even though positive proposals
were made in this regard," South African Press Association quoted
Chief Director of Foreign Trade Bahle Sibisi as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, parallel negotiations on a wine and spirit agreement
did yield some progress, said Sibisi.
</P>
<P>
"The parties will now report back to their principals on the
outcome of the meeting in order to prepare for the forthcoming
discussions between (EU) Commissioner Joao de Neus Pinheiro and
(South African) Trade Minister (Alec) Erwin," he said.
</P>
<P>
The talks, now in their 21st round, broke down last month when
the EU insisted that the names "port" and "sherry" no longer be
used by South African producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
