<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Copper Exports Down: Statistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's copper exports in
August reduced by 13 percent against that in January, falling
from 22,969 tons to 19,933 tons, according to the statistics
released by the Zambian central bank.
</P>
<P>
According to a Statistics Fortnightly obtained Friday from
Bank of Zambia, the country's central bank, copper exports have
dropped largely due to the lower price in the international
market.
</P>
<P>
The copper price in the world market fell to 1,623 U.S.
Dollars per ton in August from 1,693 Dollars in January.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, a copper-rich east African country, exported 172,740
tons of copper during the first eight months of this year while
it produced 188,454 tons of copper in the same period, said the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
The country's copper output in August rose to 27,867 tons from
20,642 tons in January, representing an increase of 35 percent,
it added.
</P>
<P>
As one of the world's largest copper companies, the Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) which is under privatization has
still held the lion's share of the country's copper production
and exports.
</P>
<P>
It produced 162,154 tons of copper in the first eight months
and sold 146,188 tons in the world market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
