<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, October 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak
has urged both Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to make compromise at Wye
Plantation peace talks.
</P>
<P>
In a signed article published here Friday by local daily
Jerusalem Post, Barak said "you must not be defeated in your
mission by political nay-sayers or the cynical practitioners of
violence... and Your compromise and responsibility will determine
the future of the Israeli and Palestinian people: coexistence or
war."
</P>
<P>
Barak called on Netanyahu and Arafat not to let the so-called
violence to deter their peace talks. "Terrorists can not be
allowed to dictate our policy and now is the time to take
courageous steps and show true leadership" in reaching agreements
concerning the peace process, he added. (Israel-Opposition
Leader-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- U.N. Resident Representative Dame Ann Hercus
launched her shuttle diplomacy between rival Greek and Turkish
Cypriot communities Friday with a meeting with Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement after her 50-minute meeting at the
Presidential Palace, the U.N. envoy said she will have her first
meeting with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash next Wednesday
before another meeting with Clerides a day later.
</P>
<P>
Hercus refrained from disclosing details of the meeting. She
has said she would be pursuing her shuttle talks in absolute
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
But press reports here said that the U.N.-sponsored on-island
shuttle talks are aimed at breaking the deadlock on the
protracted Cyprus problem. (Cyprus-Peace Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- As the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations in the
U.S. entered the second day, a Gallop poll in Israel showed Friday
that about 82 percent of the Israelis want the talks to produce an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted the result of the poll, in which 1,000
Israelis were surveyed, as showing that only 13 percent of
Israelis hope no agreement will be reached in the talks. Five
percent of those surveyed said they have no ideas.
</P>
<P>
But only a slight majority, 52 percent of those surveyed,
believed that the two sides will clinch a deal in the U.S. talks,
which started Thursday at Wye Plantation near Washington.
(Israel-Talks-Poll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey on Friday rejected an offer from Syria for
wide-range talks with Turkey, saying what concerns Ankara now is
only the issue of Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment Turkey wants to see whether Syria has put an end
to her support to terrorism," a written statement issued by the
Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Syria said that it was waiting for Turkey's reply for
the reconvention of the Syrian-Turkish joint committee, a
mechanism set up in 1992 to solve a wide range of issues between
the two countries, including the dispute of sharing water
resources from the Euphrates.
</P>
<P>
"The only issue on Turkey's agenda is support given to the
Kurdish rebels," the statement said. (Turkey-Syria-Rejection)
</P>
</TEXT>
