<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starr's Contacts with Jones Lawyers again at Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenneth Starr's
conversations with Paula Jones' lawyers in 1994 are winding up on
a list of Democratic complaints against the prosecutor in the
impeachment inquiry of U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The talks with Jones' lawyer Gilbert Davis show Starr "never
should have been appointed" to investigate the Monica Lewinsky
scandal, says Representative Barney Frank, a member of the House
of Representatives Judiciary Committee that is considering Starr's
assertions that Clinton committed impeachable offenses, the
Associated Press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Frank, a Democrat, said the Starr conversations were relevant
to the impeachment inquiry because they show "he's deeply
involved" in the Jones case long before he got permission from
Attorney General Janet Reno to expand his Whitewater investigation
to include the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
Davis said he called Starr, then a private lawyer, a half-dozen
times to seek his guidance on the constitutional question of
whether a sitting president was immune from lawsuits. Starr's view
was that the president was not.
</P>
<P>
Discussions between Starr and the Jones team first surfaced in
1994 and were brought up again by the news media in January.
National Public Radio focused new attention on the contacts
Wednesday, prompting Starr's office to issue a statement in
response.
</P>
<P>
"This office did not mislead the Department of Justice
regarding relevant facts relating to its jurisdiction, or any
expansion," Starr's office said.
</P>
<P>
Reno at her weekly news conference on Friday said, "We're
taking all the information and all the allegations and reviewing
to see if an investigation is appropriate."
</P>
<P>
At issue is whether Starr should have reported his talks with
Davis to Reno in January, when the independent counsel got
permission to look into Lewinsky, who was under subpoena in Jones'
sexual harassment lawsuit against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Frank said Starr "may have wrecked the institution of the
independent counsel beyond repair." White House spokesman Jim
Kennedy said the conversations raise "serious questions."
</P>
<P>
Senator Dick Durbin, a Democrat, urged the chairmen of the
Senate Governmental Affairs and Judiciary committees to summon
Starr before their panels.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor "failed to disclose to the attorney general his
relationship with Mr. Davis and the assistance he had given Mr.
Davis in the preparation of the Jones suit," Durbin wrote both
committees.
</P>
<P>
Representative Jerrold Nadler, a Democrat said the impeachment
inquiry, the Justice Department review and congressional oversight
hearings all were proper avenues for delving into Starr's conduct.
</P>
<P>
"Starr deserves an investigation of his own, maybe in the
context of oversight hearings next year" in the reauthorization of
the independent counsel law, said Nadler.
</P>
<P>
Jones filed her now-dismissed lawsuit on May 6, 1994, alleging
Clinton sexually harassed her in a Little Rock, Arkansas, hotel
room three years earlier when he was governor and she was a state
employee. Clinton denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department is reviewing the Starr conversations and
contacts by Starr law partner Richard Porter with New York book
agent Lucianne Goldberg, a friend of Tripp's who helped pave the
way for Tripp's cooperation with Starr's probe.
</P>
<P>
Other matters being reviewed include the taping by Starr's
investigators of a January 13 conversation between Tripp and
Lewinsky. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Summit Continues in U.S. in Less Formalities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian and Israeli
negotiators on Friday continued tough talks in Wye Mills,
Maryland, aiming at breaking the 19-month deadlock in the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
For the whole day, the delegations broke up into groups
specializing in security, economic issues, the Palestinian airport
in Gaza and setting up a safe passage for Palestinians between
Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The negotiators dropped formalities as Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat sat alone
outdoors with an interpreter under a sun umbrella for about an
hour while their negotiators tackled the disputes.
</P>
<P>
"People are dressed rather informally... It does appear that
there is a better and more constructive and more pragmatic
atmosphere to work on these problems than there had been in the
past," said State Department James Rubin at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, Netanyahu and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright had lunch at Netanyahu's quarters -- a mansion
overlooking the river at Wye Plantation.
</P>
<P>
"The informality of it all has increased and it isn't as stiff
as it used to be," Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
Rubin declined to say if the negotiators were making progress
but said the attitudes were constructive.
</P>
<P>
"We do believe that the pace of the work, the seriousness of
the work, the pragmatism that this delegation is bringing to bear,
the constructive approach is there. And whether that will be
enough is still an open question," he added.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to close a deal on Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank, coupled with Palestinian security measures to protect
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The central issue is a U.S. proposal for Israel to pull back
troops from a further 13 percent of the West Bank in exchange for
specific Palestinian assurances to crack down on militants and
give cast-iron security commitments.
</P>
<P>
Clinton had some tough words on Thursday about the need for
success, setting an ultimatum until Tuesday, according to
Palestinian sources.
</P>
<P>
If the talks collapsed, the United States would announce the
failure and would not take such an active mediating role in
future, on Palestinian official quoted Clinton as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Rubin, asked to comment, said this was news to him. "I
received pretty reasonable readouts of the various meetings... and
I never heard anyone suggesting such a thing," he added.
</P>
<P>
"What we have said is that our goal is to complete the work if
possible by Sunday. And we don't want to speculate what would
happen after Sunday," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli delegates declined to comment on this Palestinian
account, citing an agreement not to leak substance to the media.
</P>
<P>
Rubin noted that Arafat and Netanyahu have hardly met for
months and have never spent much time together.
</P>
<P>
"Now we have not only increased the frequency but turned it
into something that's more normal, something that one hopes will
make each leader understand the needs and constraints and concerns
of the other so that practical solutions can be found to very real
problems," Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Chief of Staff Reported Departing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The farewells continued on
Friday for White House chief of staff Erskine Bowles, who is
reportedly returning to North Carolina to explore a run for
governor in 2000.
</P>
<P>
A Rose Garden celebration of the budget agreement doubled as a
sendoff for Bowles.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton called the budget deal with
Republican leaders in Congress "a great closing act," for the
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
It was Bowles' second bow for leading Clinton's mostly
successful budget wrangling.
</P>
<P>
Bowles is expected to be succeeded by his deputy, John Podesta.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore said the budget negotiations would not
have succeeded without Bowles. "And we all wish you well in
whatever you do. If there's some state that needs an outstanding
chief executive, I recommend you very, very highly," Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
