<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak FM Calls for Just Settlement of Kashmir Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz Saturday called for just settlement of the Kashmir
issue, saying that there was no reason for this dispute to remain
unresolved when the world's intractable disputes had been settled.
</P>
<P>
"In a qualitatively new international environment where
seemingly intractable disputes in different parts of the world had
been resolved or were in the process of being resolved, there was
no reason why a just settlement of the Kashmir dispute should be
postponed," Aziz said in a meeting here with Indian Foreign
Secretary K. Ragunath.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister stressed the need for a sustained and
substantive dialogue between Pakistan and India to promote peace
and security in the region by resolving all outstanding issues, in
particular the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the two sides should work to identify
measures that could promote nuclear stabilization and restraint in
South Asia in order to avoid nuclear confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Foreign Secretary, however, said that India favored
normalization of relations with Pakistan without waiting for the
resolution of contentious issues.
</P>
<P>
The secretary, who is currently holding a three-day talks with
his Pakistani counterpart, said that the talks had been held in a
candid manner and that India desired continuation of this dialogue
process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
