<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Calls for Massive Turnout in Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami on Saturday called on the people to turn out vehemently to
elect the powerful Experts Assembly on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Khatami made the appeal in an interview with the state-run
television to be broadcast Saturday night, the official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The more "lively and enthusiastic the election is held, the
more it will serve the interest of the Islamic Republic and that
of the people," Khatami said, quoted by IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The call came after several candidates from the pro-Khatami
leftist and moderate factions withdrew from the campaign to
protest the disqualification of some prominent applicants by the
Guardians Council.
</P>
<P>
The conservative-dominated Guardians Council, empowered to
screen the qualification of applicants in any election by Iran's
elections law, was accused of taking side while carrying out its
mandate.
</P>
<P>
A total of 186 candidates, out of 396 applicants, were approved
by the council to run for the Experts Assembly, which serves in
each term of eight years to determine the country's supreme leader
or council of leadership.
</P>
<P>
According to Iran's constitution, the Experts Assembly also
has the right to dismiss the leader or member of the council of
leadership the incumbent fails to perform his duties.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that people have the primary role in the election
of the Experts Assembly and those elected must be accountable,
because their legitimacy emanates from the people.
</P>
<P>
"I think the Experts Assembly is where the Islamic and
republican natures of the system meet, and experts who enjoy
special status should elect a leader with specific
qualifications," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
