<HEADLINE> U.S. High School Football Player Jailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 17 (Xinhua) -- A high school football
player in Hamilton, Ohio of the United States, who was allowed to
keep playing for his school's team after pleading guilty of two
felony drug charges, is now off the team after a judge sentenced
him to one year in prison.
</P>
<P>
Wayne A. Brandon Jarrett, 18, was sentenced by Butler County
Common Pleas Judge Anthony Valen for trafficking in cocaine and
possession of cocaine. The offenses he pleaded guilty of last
month occurred when he was 17.
</P>
<P>
Jarrett had continued to start as defensive lineman for the
Princeton High School football team after his conviction. School
officials, who characterized Jarrett as a model student and
athlete, had said that neither the school district nor the Ohio
High School Athletic Association has a rule that would make
Jarrett ineligible to play because of his conviction.
</P>
<P>
Jarrett was taken to the Butler County Jail after sentencing
pending removal to the state's correctional reception center.
</P>
</TEXT>
