<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepalese Breaks Record in Climbing Mt.Qumulangma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Nepalese climber Kaji Sherpa
on Saturday scaled Mount Qumulangma, the world's highest peak, in
20 hours and 24 minutes, breaking the old record of 22 hours and
29 minutes, local Radio Nepal said.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old man started at the base camp (5,300-meter) at
four o'clock on Friday afternoon and reached the summit at 12:24
on Saturday noon, the state-run radio said.
</P>
<P>
The old record was set by a Frenchman Marc Bartard in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Detailed information is not available now.
</P>
<P>
Kaji Sherpa had planned to set a record of 18 hours on October
1, but was stalled by the weather.
</P>
<P>
This is his second attempt to conquer the 8,848-meter peak in
record time. He abandoned his first bid in 1994 after reaching a
height of 8,400 meters due to bad weather.
</P>
<P>
He had climbed this world's highest peak four times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
