<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, October 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Saturday
that his government would firmly stand by the agreements reached
by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and former Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Opening talks with visiting Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko
Komura, Primakov said he was making the statement at the
instruction of Yeltsin, the Interfax news agency
reported.(Russia-Japan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- People of Kirghizstan went to the polling stations
Saturday in a referendum on whether to introduce private land
ownership to the central Asian republic.
</P>
<P>
Turnout was high and 67.05 percent of the registered voters had
come to polling stations by noon Moscow time (08:00 GMT), the
Interfax news agency quoting Kirghiz Central Election Commission
as saying. (Kirghizstan-Referendum)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The presidents of the central Asian republics of
Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan have expressed their concern over the
situation in neighboring Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued at the end of their talks that
stretched till midnight Friday, Uzbek President Islam Karimov and
Turkmen President Saparmurat Niyazov said peace and stability in
Afghanistan should be restored as soon as possible in the
interests of the Afghan people and regional
security.(Turkmenistan-Uzbekistan-Afghanistan )
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Retired general Augusto Pinochet, who ran Chile
