<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Absolute Poverty Declines Substantially in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Absolute poverty has declined
substantially since 1992 as a result of rapid economic
development, a Ugandan minister has said.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the nation published in Saturday's New
Vision daily, Ugandan Minister of State for Finance, Planning and
Economic Development, Sam Kutesa, said that much progress was
made in the 1992-1996 period.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 46 percent of the population were not meeting their
basic requirements compared to 56 percent in 1992. This is a 10
percent decline in poverty over four years or 18 percent decline
relative to the poverty level of 1992, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Real private consumption per capita increased from 6,238
Shillings (five U.S. Dollars) to 7,320 Shillings (six Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite the strong improvements in living standards during
this period, the minister said, the poorest 20 percent became
poorer.
</P>
<P>
Although all regions had lower poverty in 1996, poverty was
more marked in the northern and eastern regions where 65.5
percent and 53.3 percent of the population respectively were
still unable to meet basic requirements.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the sharp poverty decline to economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Over this period, the gross domestic product (GDP) expanded at
a rate of 6 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program human development
index, too, indicates that Uganda continues to register a steady,
albeit slow, improvement since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP human development index (1997) ranked Uganda 159th
out of 175 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
