<HEADLINE> Iraq, Turkey Start Talks to Promote Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Turkey started
trade talks in Baghdad on Saturday to promote bilateral economic
and trade relations, the Iraqi News Agency INA reported.
</P>
<P>
INA said the Iraqi-Turkish Joint Committee for Economic
Cooperation started first round of talks, which were co-chaired
by Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rasheed and the visiting
Turkish State Minister Mehmet Batalli.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the talks, the Iraqi minister described the first
round as an important step for strengthening bilateral economic
and trade relations, saying he hoped the current visit of the
Turkish delegation would achieve its goals.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish trade delegation led by Batalli arrived here on
Friday evening to attend the meetings of the joint committee.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the talks, The Turkish minister emphasized that
the visit of the Turkish delegation reflected Turkey's desire
for increasing the volume of trade and economic exchange with
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Batalli said Turkey would take all arrangements and facilities
to further develop bilateral economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish minister also said it was necessary to lift the
over eight-year embargo imposed on Iraq, stressing that Turkey, a
close neighbor of Iraq, also had sustained grave material damage
because of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed economic sanctions on Iraq in
August 1990 following its invasion of Kuwait. The harsh sanctions
include a ban on air travel and limits on sales of oil, thus
Turkey closed the Turkish-Iraqi pipelines for exporting Iraq's
oil until December 1996 when the U.N. allowed Iraq to export
limited amount of oil to alleviate the humanitarian crisis in
this country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to INA on Friday upon arrival, Batalli said he
would discuss with Iraqi officials prospects of expanding joint
cooperation in economic and trade areas.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-Iraqi Joint Committee of Economic cooperation held
its last meetings in December 1996 in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying Batalli in the trade delegation are 21 members
from government ministries, chamber of commerce and big companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
