<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Organisms Millions of Years Old Possible in Antarctic Ice Lake (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from France, Russia,
and the United States have found an ice lake beneath 3,700 meters
of ice in the Antarctic where they think old organisms may exist.
</P>
<P>
The 200 km by 50 km lake is 600 meters deep at the deepest and
is the largest and oldest ice lake among those that have been
discovered in the Antarctic, according to one of the
glaciologists, J.R. Petit from France.
</P>
<P>
Petit told a recent international Antarctic glaciology
symposium in Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's Gansu Province
that they found the lake when they were drilling for ice cores at
Russia's Vostok Station early this year, and a Russian scientist
has discovered live microorganisms in a 5,000-year-old ice core
sample.
</P>
<P>
At first, the Russian found some dust in the ice core, and then
he discovered live microorganisms existing in five percent of the
dust.
</P>
<P>
"We think that there must be live beings aged from one million
to even 10 million years old in the deeper ice layer or in the
lake," Petit said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists believe that no larger living beings exist in the
lake because they could not stand the pressure and the clean water
has no sugar or food to sustain life.
</P>
<P>
Petit said that it is difficult for the microorganisms to live
in the lake as well, but they struggle by on some special
materials put out by volcanos in the same historical era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
