<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Organism Millions of Years Old Possible in Antarctic Ice Lake (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The study on these possible living beings several million years
in the lake will provide valuable clues for research on the
origins of life and the possibility of life in outer space, Petit
said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the United States plan to put a sound device in
the lake to do research in the next four years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some minerals found at the end of the ice core indicate that
there are abundant rocks at the bottom of the lake, and Petit
regards this as his latest discovery. Another rare phenomenon is
that the 200-meter-thick ice layer over the lake surface is
directly formed by frozen lake water.
</P>
<P>
Most glaciers in the area are usually formed by a lot of
accumulating snow piles that becomes harder year after year, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
They started ice core drilling at Vostok 10 years ago
originally for research on climate and environmental changes in
the Antarctic during the past 400,000 years, he says. When they
got more than three kilometers deep, they inferred from the rising
temperature and radar data that there must be a lake under the ice
layer, the scientist recalls.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the lake from being polluted, they stopped drilling
at a depth of 3,623 meters, 127 meters from the lake surface,
Petit said, adding that the ice core is so far the deepest in the
Antarctic, and the earliest data they can come up with goes back
400,000 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
