<HEADLINE> Meteor Storm Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese stargazers will be able
to see a meteor storm with the naked eye at 2:00-4:00 a.m. the
morning of November 18, Chinese astronomers say.
</P>
<P>
They made the announcement yesterday in Nanjing, the capital of
east China's Jiangsu Province, at a seminar on meteor storms,
held October 14-16.
</P>
<P>
This meteor storm, in the constellation Leo, is the first
visible one in China in nearly 100 years. Thousands of meteors are
expected to emerge every hour, the astronomers said.
</P>
<P>
The event will be significant for space monitoring, preventing
space disasters, telecommunications security, and the relations
between celestial bodies in the solar system, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers from Holland, the United States, France, and
elsewhere will come to witness it in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
