<HEADLINE> Chinese Shut Out from World Cup Table Tennis Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Cao Jianjie
</P>
<P>
SHANTOU, China, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese table tennis
fans got used to winning and accepted nothing less. That was why
they booed and gibed at the players who failed to live up to
their expectation.
</P>
<P>
China's best trio -- Kong Linghui, world No. 2, Liu Guoliang,
No.4, and Ma Lin, No.11, all lost on the third day of the World
Cup table tennis tournament Saturday afternoon, seeing their
lower-ranked rivals sail into Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese players are weak in mentality, consistency and
adaptability at their opponents' styles," said Li Furong, vice
president of the Chinese Table Tennis Association.
</P>
<P>
World No. 9 Kim Taek Soo, who struggled in his group matches
but upset Sweden's reigning world champion Jan-Ove Waldner in the
quarter-finals, combined his usual array of table tennis wares to
deadly effect, routing Liu 21-15, 21-14, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
Liu moved into the semifinals at the expense of Ma Lin.
</P>
<P>
World No. 14 Jorg Rosskopf, who suffered a whitewash by Liu in
a group match but nipped Kong in a fight for a semifinal berth,
blanked 1993 and 1997 World Cup winner Zoran Primorac of Croatia
21-12, 21-15, 21-18 to reach the final.
</P>
<P>
Kim stunned Chinese double Olympic gold medalist with vicious
loops, deft blocks and consistent rallies.
</P>
<P>
"It's unbelievable," said Liu after the match. "Kim played so
well and he gave me a lot of pressure throughout the match."
</P>
<P>
Kim, who had only won four out of his 13 encounters with Liu
before this match, said he was just one step away from the World
Cup title and he would never let the chance slip easily.
</P>
<P>
"I feel so good now and I promise, I will bring out the best
in the final," he said.
</P>
<P>
Primorac's jubilation over his win over Belarus' world No. 1
Vladimir Samsonov earlier this afternoon was cut short as he
failed to beat the jinx in the game against Rosskopf.
</P>
<P>
No one has ever won the World Cup for the second straight time.
</P>
<P>
The world fifth-ranked Croatian looked jaded against the
inspired Rosskopf, whose ferocious backhand is stronger than many
of his peer's forehand.
</P>
<P>
Neither Rosskopf nor Kim has won the World Cup. Their best
performance in the annual event was second.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf said he had fifty-fifty chance against Kim in the
final but would "fight to the last".
</P>
<P>
China has won the World Cup for 10 times in the previous 18
versions. Sweden has won three times with Croatia twice, France,
Poland and Hungary once. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
