<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kirghizstan Holds Referendum on Private Land Ownership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 17 (Xinhua) -- People of Kirghizstan went to
the polling stations Saturday in a referendum on whether to
introduce private land ownership to the central Asian republic.
</P>
<P>
Turnout was high and 67.05 percent of the registered voters had
come to polling stations by noon Moscow time (08:00 GMT), the
Interfax news agency quoting Kirghiz Central Election Commission
as saying.
</P>
<P>
A referendum is valid in Kirghizstan if no less than 51 percent
of the registered 2.254 million voters turn up, the commission
said.
</P>
<P>
Kirghiz President Askar Akayev said earlier Saturday that the
referendum, on amendments to the constitution, would determine the
future of the country and the presidency.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not expect the voters to support his ideas
unanimously but "it would be excellent" if two thirds of the
voters backed the amendments.
</P>
<P>
If the amendments are approved, Kirghiz said, land plots should
also be given to doctors, school teachers and social workers in
the villages in order to avoid public discontent.
</P>
<P>
"We should do our best to form a middle class not only in the
cities but also in the villages," Interfax quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the amendments to the constitution would give an
impetus to democratic reforms in the country and prove a good
model for other members of the Commonwealth of Independent
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
