<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) is leading the world in
vehicle-population ratio of 22 vehicles per each 100 people,
according to a report released on the sidelines of the current
international vehicle fair in Sharjah.
</P>
<P>
The report by Sharjah chamber of commerce, the fair organizer,
said the number of vehicles in UAE grew from 350,000 in 1995 to
575,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
London-based "Al Hayat" Arabic newspaper Saturday quoted the
report as saying the figure is expected to increase in view of the
fact of high percentage of population under the driving license
age.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemen General Authority of Communications (YGAV)
demanded supplying 2,000 street telephone stands through the 1998
bidding.
</P>
<P>
According to Cairo-based "Al Alam Al Youm" newspaper Saturday,
the YGAV conditioned the stands should be made of stainless steel
and the applying companies should pay bidding fees of 3.5 percent
of total merchandise offered.
</P>
<P>
The offers should be sent no later than November, 1998.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Moroccan National Company of Roads solicited the
international companies for construction of Sedi Yamani-Tangers
highway, north to the capital city of Rabat, according to
Saturday's "Al Alam Al Youm" newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The economic newspaper quoted the company as saying the segment
is the last of the Casablanca-Tangers highway linking Africa and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Algeria has signed an agreement
regulating pharmaceutical trade between the two countries, reported
Saturday's "Al Ahram" newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaily said the
agreement comprised the coordination in the field of
standardization, considering a bilateral free trade zone, in
addition to boosting co-operation between Egypt's international
trade representing office and the Algeria's chamber of trade and
investment, information exchange, and enhancing joint investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
