<HEADLINE> Primakov: Russia to Stick to Accords With Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said Saturday that his government would firmly stand by
the agreements reached by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
former Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Opening talks with visiting Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko
Komura, Primakov said he was making the statement at the
instruction of Yeltsin, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Komura arrived here Friday night on a 24-hour visit designed to
prepare for the next Russian-Japanese summit scheduled for
November.
</P>
<P>
He said the new Russian Cabinet would be a reliable partner for
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Later Saturday, Komura will also meet with Russian First
Deputy Prime Minister Yuri Maslyukov, co-chairman of the
Russian-Japanese Commission for Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Moscow in the evening, Komura is also expected
to meet with Yuri Luzhkov, the Moscow mayor who heads the
non-governmental Russian-Japanese Committee for the 21st Century,
the Interfax said. 
