<HEADLINE> Flood Hits Bali, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Flood brought by heavy rains
swept away dozens of houses and tens of vehicles in Jembrana
district in Indonesia's western Bali Friday, Antara News Agency
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The water rose up to 1.5 meters high, prompting the people to
flee to safer places," local administration's spokesman Semadi
Arsana said.
</P>
<P>
The flood, which hit three villages in Pekutatan subdistrict,
also destroyed a water pipeline and caused a short circuit that
sparked a fire and burned down a kiosk, he said.
</P>
<P>
Material losses are expected to run into one billion rupiah
(100,000 U.S. dollars), but no casualty was reported.
</P>
<P>
It was the second flood to hit the district this week.
</P>
<P>
On October 14, flood also hit three villages in Mandoyo
subdistrict and a village in Negara subdistrict. One villager was
killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
