<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No deadlock in Pak-India Talks on Kashmir: Ragunath </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Indian Foreign Secretary K.
Ragunath said here Saturday that there was no deadlock in the
talks between India and Pakistan over the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
"It is not the question of total deadlock, we are going to
continue our discussions," he said at a joint press briefing after
having about three-hour exclusive talks on the thorny Kashmir
issue with his Pakistani counterpart Shamshad Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
The Indian foreign secretary declined to give direct answer to
a question that whether there was any deadline set by India to
resolve this long-standing issue.
</P>
<P>
"There are many possibilities for improving the relations for
which you have to look at the relations in their totality and in
all aspects," Ragunath said, adding, "of course addressing of the
outstanding issues is one of the aspects."
</P>
<P>
When asked to spell out India's position on the Kashmir issue,
Ragunath said, "our position on these issues have been amply made
clear."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about thinning out of the Indian
troops in India-held Kashmir, he said, "we have heard these kinds
of suggestions."
</P>
<P>
"Our position on it is known that it is linked to some other
actions which we expect from Pakistan," he said, adding that
"these are the matters which are open for discussion."
</P>
<P>
Asked about Pakistan's decision to unilaterally release all
Indian civilian prisoners in Pakistan, Ragunath said New Delhi is
in touch with Islamabad on this matter and "necessary steps will
be taken". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
