<HEADLINE> Pakistan Rules Out Idea of No-first Use of Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Saturday ruled
out the proposal of no-first use of nuclear weapons as "outdated."
</P>
<P>
"That is an outdated concept in any case - even in the cold
war context of between NATO and WARSAW Pact this concept was never
recognized as relevant - so there is no question of accepting this
irrelevant concept," Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad
said while replying to reporter's questions after the joint
briefing held at the end of Pak-Indian talks on Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
The talks on the contentious Jammu and Kashmir dispute between
Shamshad Ahmad and his Indian counterpart K Ragunath followed
Friday's talks on issues of peace and security.
</P>
<P>
When asked for an alternative Pakistani proposal, he said, "we
have to develop a nuclear doctrine on the basis of minimum nuclear
deterrence capability."
</P>
<P>
Shamshad said that Pakistan has given some "specific ideas" to
India on the need for having a "regime of mutual restraint and
stabilization."
</P>
<P>
Replying to another question on Islamabad's proposal on non-
aggression pact, he stated that "we have left this proposal at the
table - you can call it a non-aggression pact or non-use of force
or avoidance of conflict."
</P>
<P>
The purpose of such a pact, he said, is to avoid a "devastating
conflict" in the changed environment in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
