<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Asks Syria to Drive out PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel has asked Syria to drive Turkey's outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) out of the country if it wants better
relations.
</P>
<P>
Local Milliyet newspaper Saturday quoted Demirel as saying late
Friday night that "the place to shelter terrorists and the leader
(of PKK) is Syria. What Syria will do is to drive them out of the
country."
</P>
<P>
"The situation which disturbs Turkey is the situation which
Syria supports terrorism," said Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry Friday issued a statement rejecting
an offer of Syria for wide-range talks with Turkey. It said what
concerns Ankara now is only the issue of Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment Turkey wants to see whether Syria has put an end
to her support to terrorism," added the statement.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Turkey and Syria have always been
troublesome. Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring the PKK,
which has been fighting since 1984 for autonomy of the Kurdish
minority in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria, denying the charges, repeatedly voiced its concern and
fear over Turkey's close military alliance with Israel that
threats Arab security.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has stepped up a war of words against Syria recently and
Ankara's war-like rhetoric has aroused fears of a regional
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
and Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi have visited Turkey
and Syria to try to persuade the two neighbors to solve their
dispute through dialog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 South, South-East Asian Countries Likely to Set Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Five South and Southeast Asian
countries may decide to connect their capitals through setting up
a "common airline" and physically inter-link their nations through
a trans-Asian highway.
</P>
<P>
Both the ideas are likely to receive a go-ahead at the
forthcoming ministerial BIMSTEC (the Bangladesh, Indian, Myanmar,
Sri Lanka, Thailand Economic Cooperation) meeting, The Daily Star
newspaper reported Saturday, quoting diplomatic sources.
</P>
<P>
The BIMSTEC, a new regional grouping comprising five countries
bordering the Bay of Bengal and was launched in the Thai capital
of Bangkok on June 6 last year, is expected to hold its first
ministerial meeting in Dhaka in December.
</P>
<P>
Four littoral countries of the Bay of Bengal -- Bangladesh,
India, Sri Lanka and Thailand -- had initially started the
grouping called BISTEC. Later at a ministerial-level meeting held
on December 22 last year, the four founding members agreed to
admit Myanmar, and it is now called BIMSTEC.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming meeting is expected to identify the thrust
sectors of the grouping, and plans are on the anvil to find ways
and means to focus on increasing trade, investment, tourism and
exchange of scientific data including meteorological data, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be also expected to draw up a possible list of
tariff concessions with the aim of creating a free trade zone in
the BIMSTEC countries in future, they stated.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong port, the largest sea-port of Bangladesh, is
likely to receive special focus for being propped up as a gateway
for boosting cargo trade and providing more trans-shipment,
refueling and warehousing facilities to the countries, and it may
be developed as a regional trade hub and a major gateway to the
Bay of Bengal, said Bangladeshi State Minister for Foreign Affairs
Abul Hasan Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the BIMSTEC has authorized an organization to conduct
a study for construction of a trans-Asian highway linking all the
five countries, and stretches of the highway already exist and it
is a matter of linking up and providing facilitation services, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 businessmen from the five countries at their March 6-7
meeting this year in Bangkok formed an expert group with former
president of the Dhaka Chamber of Commerce and Industries as first
chairman of the BIMSTEC economic forum.
</P>
<P>
The original idea of the grouping was mooted by Bangladesh, Sri
Lanka, India and Thailand and was initially referred to as the
"Bay of Bengal Economic Cooperation Organization." And the
regional alliance was initiated considering the great potential of
increasing trade within these countries by taking advantage of the
geographical proximity of the countries of the Bay of Bengal
region and the eastern coast of the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The BIMSTEC is also being seen as a bridge between three SAARC
(South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation) countries --
Bangladesh, India and Sri Lanka -- and two ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) countries -- Thailand and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
"The BIMSTEC is in fact the first and only institutional link
between SAARC and the ASEAN," Hasan Chowdhury observed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shamshad: Quick Solution to Kashmir Dispute Unrealistic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad said here Saturday that it would be unrealistic to
expect any quick solution to the contentious Kashmir dispute
between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad was talking to reporters at a briefing here Saturday
afternoon at the conclusion of the second session of talks with
Indian Foreign Secretary K. Ragunath.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two sides agreed to continue their
discussions on the Kashmir issue in the next round of talks whose
timing would be announced Sunday in the final statement.
</P>
<P>
"It would have been unrealistic on any body's part to expect
that we will come out from this short session with any concrete
progress on the one of the most complex issues which the world is
facing today and the issue which is the cause of serious peace and
security problems in this part of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistani and Indian delegations have held "useful
exchange of views in the very frank and candid manner" on the
50-year-old dispute during Saturday's talks.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides "did exchange some ideas on how to approach to
the final settlement of Jammu and Kashmir issue and of course this
requires further detailed discussion," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the issue will take considerable time and attention
from both sides and that is why we have decided that we will
resume discussions on this subject in the next round of talks."
</P>
<P>
Indian foreign secretary Ragunath said at the briefing that "we
have begun the discussions and will continue exchange of
conceptions."
</P>
<P>
"Yet it is not occasion to spell out these conceptions we have
discussed. The basic positions (of the two sides) are known," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Shamshad and Ragunath pondered over the issues of
the regional peace and security and exchanged "substantive
proposals" on the confidence building measures between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two senior diplomats are to wrap up their current round of
talks and issue a final statement on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
