<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim, Rosskopf Cruise into World Cup Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, China, October 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Kim Taek
Soo and German Jorg Rosskopf beat their more fancied rivals on
Saturday to move into the World Cup table tennis final which has
a 38,000 U.S. dollars champion's purse at stake.
</P>
<P>
The world No. 9 Kim, who struggled in his group matches but
upset world champion Jan-Ove Waldner of Sweden in the
quarter-finals,routed the world No. 4 Chinese fast-attacker Liu
Guoliang, 21-15, 21-14, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf, who suffered a whitewash by Liu in a group match but
nipped world No. 2 Chinese Kong Linghui in a fight for a
semifinal berth, blanked 1993 and 1997 World Cup winner Zoran
Primorac of Croatia 21-12, 21-15, 21-18.
</P>
<P>
Kim stunned China's double Olympic gold medalist with vicious
loops, deft blocks and consistent rallies.
</P>
<P>
"It's unbelievable," said Liu after the match. "Kim played so
well and gave me a lot of pressure throughout the match."
</P>
<P>
Kim, who had only won four games in his 13 encounters with Liu
before this match, said he was just one step away from the World
Cup and he wouldn't let the chance slip easily.
</P>
<P>
"I feel so good now and I promise, I will bring out the best
in the final," he said.
</P>
<P>
Primorac, who outlasted world No. 1 Vladimir Samsonov of
Belarus 3-1 in the quarter-finals, looked jaded against the
inspired Rosskopf.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf said he had fifty-fifty chance against Kim in the
final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
