<HEADLINE> Lebanese Companies to Attend Baghdad Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese companies will take
part in Baghdad Trade Fair for the first time since the end of the
1991 Gulf War, the Daily Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 businessmen from 63 industrial and agricultural
companies are expected to take part in the six-day trade fair
which opens on October 25.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese companies have booked 1,000 square meters of space
at the Baghdad International Exhibition Center, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said that 15 trucks loaded with Lebanese goods have
already set off for Baghdad with 10 more to follow. The total
value of Lebanese products is estimated at more than 3 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, authorized by the United Nations to buy 3.5 billion
dollars worth of goods, medications and goods under the
oil-for-food deal, agreed to buy 50 million dollars worth of
agricultural products from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The products will be transported through Syria and Jordan.
U.N. observers will inspect all goods before they enter Iraq to
ensure they are not in violation of the U.N. resolutions on
economic sanctions on Iraq for its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Among the Lebanese products to be put on display are
canned food, fruit, vegetables, furniture, sanitary equipment,
ceramics, house appliance and beverages.
</P>
<P>
Arak, Lebanon's traditional alcoholic drink, will also be
offered for sale in Baghdad in an attempt to re-enter a
profitable market. Iraq was the biggest foreign customer for
Lebanese Arak before the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Jaques Sarraf, President of the Lebanese Industrial
Association, is due to travel to Baghdad to hold talks with
Iraqi business leaders during the fair in a bid to seek a
bigger Lebanese share in the oil-for-food deal, the paper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
