<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, October 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad said
Saturday that he and his Indian counterpart K. Ragunath were
endeavoring to bring about positive results from the on-going
talks.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad and Ragunath devoted their first day of talks Friday
to the issues of peace and security which top the 8-point agenda
agreed by the two sides during their talks here last June. The
two senior diplomats would take up the contentious Kashmir issue
Saturday. (Pakistan-India-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro on Friday asked
Massimo D'Alema, the leader of the Left Democrats, to try to form
a new governing majority.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema, who leads the largest party in the center-left Olive
Tree alliance, accepted the mandate Friday evening. If D'Alema
succeeds, he will become the first former Communist to head a
government in Italy. D'Alema told reporters that he would proceed
with "great caution" in his attempt to form a "strong and stable"
government. (Italy-Government)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Twenty seven Tamil rebel child conscripts, who had
tried to give themselves up to government troops in north of Sri
Lanka, were shot dead by the rebel hierarchy Friday, according to
reports reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The conscripts who are from Jaffna peninsula, had been forcibly
recruited by the rebels, reports quoted security sources as
saying. (Sri Lanka-Tamil Rebels)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine's Supreme Soviet (parliament) ratified on
Friday the Chemical Weapons Convention, which bans the design,
production, accumulation and use of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that the ratification came
after a failed attempt of the parliament on October 6 to ratify
the convention when some parliament members feared for a possible
international control over chemical production in Ukraine.
However, this time the 450-member parliament ratified the
Convention with 285 for and 16 against. (Ukraine-Chemical Weapons)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslavia on Friday signed the agreement on a
verification mission in Kosovo with the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Yugoslavia will allow 2,000 unarmed
observers from the 54-nation OSCE into Kosovo to verify its
compliance with U.N. resolutions, which called for the withdrawal
of the Yugoslav army and special police forces from the Kosovo
province. (Yugoslavia-OSCE) 
</P>
