<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Gradually Open Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- China will gradually open its
financial sector, meanwhile establish an efficient supervisory
mechanism, said Liu Mingkang, deputy president of the People's Bank
of China.
</P>
<P>
Liu made the remarks at the fair of foreign economic and
technological co-operation in the central and western regions,
which opened in Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan
Province, today.
</P>
<P>
Granting more foreign financial institutions access to Chinese
market should come in line with China's financial supervision
capacity, and further opening up the nation's financial industry
to the outside world means permission on the proper increase of
the number of foreign financial institutions launching business in
China, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that foreign financial institutions
had opened 178 operational establishments in China by June, and
the People's Bank of China has authorized Shanghai and Shenzhen to
experiment with business by foreign banks in renminbi (RMB),
China's currency.
</P>
<P>
"China will not depreciate RMB," Liu emphasized, adding that
China is able to adhere to the non-devaluation stance because of
the backing of its economic strength and managerial expertise.
</P>
<P>
China will encourage export and foreign investment to cope with
the fallout of the Southeast Asian economic crisis, he said, a
series of steps will be taken to improve the financial service
sector, strengthen cooperation between banks and trade sectors,
and provide more support for propping up the foreign trade
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
