<HEADLINE> Pak, India Try to Bring About Positive Results From Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad said on Saturday that he and his Indian counterpart
K. Ragunath were endeavoring to bring about positive results from
the on-going talks.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters before entering into talks for the second
day, Shamshad said that substantive proposals pertaining to issues
of peace and security were exchanged in Friday's talks.
</P>
<P>
"But I cannot say at the moment if we can reach any agreement.
We are still in a process," he said. "We are endeavoring to bring
about a positive final statement on Sunday."
</P>
<P>
Shamshad and Ragunath Friday devoted their first day of talks
to the issues of peace and security which top the 8-point agenda
agreed by the two sides during their talks here last June.
</P>
<P>
The two senior diplomats would take up the contentious Kashmir
issue on Saturday for an exclusive discussion for the first time
in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally the two sides will reiterate each other's known
positions on the Kashmir dispute, however we are encouraged by the
vision of the two prime ministers," Shamshad said.
</P>
<P>
"For us, it is not only a vision but a mandate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Indian Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee have recently agreed to revive the bilateral
high-level dialogue stalled last September as the leaders saw the
necessity for an environment for durable peace and peaceful
settlement of the Jammu and Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
The dispute has rendered all the reconciliation efforts by
Islamabad and New Delhi fruitless because of the two sides'
seemingly uncompromising positions.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan insists that the core issue of Kashmir should be
resolved before any other agreements can be reached while India
favors first taking up commercial and trade issues, saying the
status of Kashmir is not negotiable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
