<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four-Step Outlines Half Done </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By sportswriter Liu Guang
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua)-- A decade ago a sports official
outlined the future of chess in China in a program which aim to
sweep all the four chess titles to its credit on a four-step
basis.
</P>
<P>
The idea was dismissed as a fat chance for Europe, the
traditional chess powerhouse, have kept an undisputedly firm grip
on chess titles for decades.
</P>
<P>
The potential challenge was ignored until the just-concluded
world chess Olympiade in Elista where four Chinese young women cri
 sply snapped the winning streak of the Europeans with their
first women's team title ever to their crown.
</P>
<P>
Led by Xie Jun, the double world champion, the team capped
their ten years' relentless efforts by cruising to the victory
through thirteen rounds of wit campaign with an unbeatable 29
total points advantage over the closest rivals.
</P>
<P>
Under the inspiration from the women's side, China's men team
also broke new grounds as they improved to their best fifth place
ever, a remarkable progress in the heavy competition in men's
field.
</P>
<P>
Chen Zude, who headed the delegation to the event, could not
calm himself when realising the outline he made has been half
finished.
</P>
<P>
"This ushered in a new beginning for chess, and it also marked
a significant milestone for the high-riding Chinese team who make
its debut in 1980."
</P>
<P>
Wang Jia, vice president of China's Chess Association, said
that the success lies chiefly with the unmatched high quality of
the chess players they fielded.
</P>
<P>
"First this is a well-disciplined and united squad, and they
all have higher education backgrounds. Thirdly they are also
well-balanced by their different styles and possessed tested
mental quality."
</P>
<P>
The outfit, aged 24 on average, displayed more cutting edge
than the chess power Georgia whose aged lineup was embarrassed
into the late stage of the thirteen round event when feeling hard
to concentrate on the game, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
"Young as they are, the Chinese team did not in the least fall
short of the expericence," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
The lineup was all made up of grandmasters on international
level. Xie Jun was crowned with two-time world champion, Wang
Ping ever qualified for the world champion candidacy competition,
and the other two are also champions in world collegiate event or
junior champions.
</P>
<P>
Until now the first two steps of the outline -- the women's
individual title and the women's team title -- has come into
reality.
</P>
<P>
China chess reached its first milestone when Xie Jun claimed
the women's individual title in 1991 in the world women's chess
championshiop, becoming the first non-Europe champion in chess
history. The 28-year-old also retained her title in 1993.
</P>
<P>
What about the last two steps -- the men's team title and the
individual title?
</P>
<P>
Chen Zude, the straightspoken sport offical, appeared a little
cautious in shedding light on the future.
</P>
<P>
"It is not easy for us Chinese, because chess has been part of
the western civilisation, the East has not failed to pose a
serious challenge to the dominance of the West."
</P>
<P>
But the 33rd Olympiade has unfolded a promising prospect for
the Chinese men, who proved their strength on a step-by-step
pursuit.
</P>
<P>
China went through to the fifth place in the men's field with
110 teams participating, although their world ranking points pla
ced only 35th.
</P>
<P>
They came away with a record of eight wins, three ties and two
losses in 13 matches, including the victory over the finally
fourth-placed Israel and two draws each with the runner-up United
States and third-placed Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Chen expressed his determination that men's team should do as
well as the women.
</P>
<P>
"Anyway men's chess is more significant,"said Chen. "We will
try although it is much harder." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
