<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-impeachment Internet Petition Draws A Quarter Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A Web site which is
building a petition to end impeachment proceedings against
President Bill Clinton announced Friday that it has gathered
250,000 signatures online among the Americans.
</P>
<P>
The Web site "moveon.org" was launched September 22 by a couple
in California, Joan Blades and Wes Boyd who are co-founders of the
software firm Berkeley Systems. It urges the U.S. Congress to
"immediately censure President Clinton and move on to pressing
issues facing the country."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the quarter million signatures in three weeks, the
site developers said that it is the largest "cyber-petition" in
history. "The polls are saying it, and so have a quarter million
of our signers -- it's time to move on," they said in the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
The site cost 89.50 U.S. dollars to start. Visitors to the site
were asked to give their names, e-mail address, Zip codes and, if
they wanted, a comment.
</P>
<P>
To advertise the site, the couple sent e-mail to about 80
friends and acquaintances, asking them to add their names and pass
on the information.
</P>
<P>
In the first 24 hours, the site had more than 500
responses. Two weeks later, more than 175,000 Americans signed.
</P>
<P>
The site developers hope to get one, two or three million
names. But observers say it is not clear that signatures gathered
over the Net are taken seriously in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Owners, Players Make Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- NBA owners agreed Friday to
accept the union's concept of a luxury tax on some contracts to
see if such a system will slow salary growth.
</P>
<P>
This is a sign of progress in the lockout since July 1.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to try it the union's way, but they have to
agree that if it doesn't work, we then have to try it our way,
"deputy commissioner Russ Granik said.
</P>
<P>
The league asked for a two-year trial, with higher tax rates
and a lower threshold than the union had proposed. A hard salary
cap would be taken in the 2000-21 season if the percentage of
league revenue devoted to salaries failed to drop from 57 percent
to 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
"It appears at a quick glance to be a step backward. More
onerous than the proposal we received from them on September 24,"
union director Billy Hunter said. "It may be disguised in terms
of a tax, but it is in fact a hard cap."
</P>
<P>
According to the league's projections, the tax would have no
impact on 85 percent of future player contracts.
</P>
<P>
The tax rate would be 50 percent of the amount over 2.6
million U.S. dollars for all contracts worth up to 10 million
dollars annually. For contracts worth between 10 million dollars
and 15 million dollars annually. For contracts worth between 10
million dollars and 15 million dollars, the tax would be 100
percent, between 15 million dollars and 20 million dollars, 150
percent, and for contracts worth more than 20 million dollars,
200 percent, Granik said.
</P>
<P>
There was no decision Friday from John Feerick on the issue of
whether players with guaranteed contracts must be paid during the
lockout.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
