<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Upsets Waldner in World Cup Quarter-finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, China, October 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Kim Taek
Soo humiliated reigning world champion Jan-Ove Waldner, joining
Zoran Primorac in the semi-finals of the World Cup table tennis
tournament here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old Kim, the ninth-ranked player whose dedication
and attitude is an example to all, rallied to beat the
33-year-old Swede, the only player who has won a "grand slam" of
the Olympic, World Championship and World Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
After losing the first bet 13-21, Kim, quick on his feet with
a powerful right-handed attacking game, came from 13-17 down to
snatch the second set 22-20.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean turned up the heat by taking the following
sets 21-19, 21-13.
</P>
<P>
"I changed service in the second set and it came troubles to
Waldner," Kim said after the match.
</P>
<P>
Defending World Cup champion Primorac of Croatia brought down
world No.1 ranked Samsonov of Belarus, making the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
It seemed Samsonov was not in form as Primorac blasted winner
after winner for a 9-21, 21-15, 21-15, 23-21 victory.
</P>
<P>
In the other quarter-final games, Chinese Liu Guoliang edged
out teammate Ma Lin 22-20, 21-16, 17-21, 14-21, 21-17, and
Germany's Jorg Rosskopf downed World No.2 Kong Linghui 21-12,
14-21, 21-19, 11-21, 21-18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
