<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stone Altar Found in Mysterious Underground Chamber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The door of a newly-discovered
underground chamber under an ancient Chinese tower was opened by
archeologists at noon today, revealing a small sariras-enshrining
chamber.
</P>
<P>
After the 1 meter-wide, 0.8 meter-high chamber door was opened,
a stone sariras-worshipping altar, a censer, and a stone tablet
came to light.
</P>
<P>
"We have never seen such a big sariras-worshiping alter," Han
Wei, a researcher with local cultural relic research institute
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The censer was put on top of the about 1 meter-long, 1.5
meter-wide sariras-worshiping alter. After reading characters on
the stone tablet, Han told reporters a sariras--a combination of
bone ashes of eminent Buddhist monks dating back about 1,400
years--may be worshiped inside the alter.
</P>
<P>
The chamber was discovered beneath the 1,400-year-old Fawang
Tower in the southern part of Zhouzhi County in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province, a place 80 kilometers away from the provincial
capital of Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
The 30-meter-high Fawang Tower was built in 601 by Yang Jian,
an emperor of the Sui Dynasty (581-618). He built 31 towers to
bury 31 sariras in 601. These sariras were called as "Renshou
sariras".
</P>
<P>
"This tower was the only one still preserved till today, and the
sariras inside the tower was one of the 'Renshou sariras'" said
Han.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists will open the stone box to let the sariras
presumed to be preserved inside the alter come to light. But
before that, a series of precaution steps must be taken to protect
the precious sariras from damages to be brought by exposures.
</P>
<P>
The local government decided to move the tower to make way for
the construction of a reservoir which is to bring relief to water
shortages in the provincial capital city. With the approval of the
State Council, the task began in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Today's excavation was broadcast live by the China Central
Television (CCTV), the first time the CCTV live broadcasts
excavation process of an archeological finding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
