<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Start Post-Flood Farming in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi farmers have started
farming in full swing after the recent severe flood under a
massive program taken up by the Department of Agricultural
Extension (DAE) to cultivate different kinds of winter crops and
vegetables on six million hectares of land in the country.
</P>
<P>
The irrigated rice cultivation target has been fixed at 3.05
million hectares, wheat cultivation program has been set at 0.85
hectares, while maize, potato, sweet potato and other crops will
be cultivated on the 1.8 million hectares, The New Nation
newspaper Saturday quoted an DAE source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a program has also been taken by the DAE to cultivate
winter vegetables on 0.3 million hectares of land with production
target of 4.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Necessary measures have been taken to give loans, supply high
yielding varieties of seeds, fertilizer, insecticides and other
necessary inputs to the farmers of the flood-affected districts
for the successful implementation of the scheme, he stated.
</P>
<P>
It needs 666 tons of seeds to implement the program, and the
Bangladesh Agricultural Development Corporation will supply
high-yielding-variety seeds to the growers while the Bangladesh
Krishi (agricultural) Bank would arrange cash loans, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sowing of seeks will commence from November and continue till
the end of December.
</P>
<P>
The recent ten-week-long devastating floods had destroyed crops
on 0.85 million hectares of land in the country's 52
severely-affected districts, causing a loss of about 40 billion
taka (about 851.1 million U.S. dollars), while farmers lost over
3.5 million tons of crops including 2 million tons of rice,
according the latest figures issued by the DAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
