<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Urges Peace Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn
Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army, reacting to
Friday's award of the Nobel Peace Prize, said the biggest prize
was the peace process itself.
</P>
<P>
"The big prize is the peace settlement, and that's the prize
for all of us to keep our eyes on," said Adams at a news
conference in New York.
</P>
<P>
"I am not disappointed, I'm pleased for John Hume, and I hope
David Trimble will accept the responsibilities which go along with
these recognitions," Adams, who is on a week-long tour of the
northeastern United States.
</P>
<P>
Nobel Peace Prize was awarded to Hume, 61, head of the main
Roman Catholic nationalist party in Northern Ireland, and Trimble,
54, leader of the biggest Protestant party that wants the province
to remain under British rule.
</P>
<P>
Adams said he hoped the recognition would serve as "a spur and
an incentive to those who may be reluctant or those who may be
hanging back and those who may be delaying and those who may be
undecided about the future."
</P>
<P>
He added that the "only question" about the peace process and
its timetable was coming from Trimble's Ulster Unionist Party.
</P>
<P>
"So it's entirely within Mr. Trimble's gift as a leader of his
party and as a signatory to the agreement to ensure that indeed
this is not premature but is simply the precursor to his joining
with the rest of us... and moving forward with all speed," Adams
said.
</P>
<P>
He also said Sinn Fein had made as large a contribution to the
peace agreement as had other parties in the process.
</P>
<P>
"I think I have worked as hard," Adams said, "We have all
worked hard. The recognition that Sinn Fein has worked as hard
comes from our having increased our vote in the last election."
</P>
</TEXT>
