<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Swift OSCE Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Italy's acting foreign minister
Lamberto Dini Friday urged the swiftest possible deployment of
international observers in Kosovo to verify Yugoslavia's
compliance with agreed terms on ending the crisis there.
</P>
<P>
Reporting to the cabinet on Kosovo developments and Thursday's
meeting of the Contact Group, Dini highlighted the importance of
the mission from the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE), whose formal mandate was signed in Belgrade Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 2,000-strong OSCE team of observers is charged with
monitoring the withdrawal of Serb special forces and the return of
aid workers to the area, where thousands of displaced Kosovo
residents are facing a humanitarian disaster as a Balkan winter
approaches.
</P>
<P>
Dini noted that the Italian government's development aid
department has already sent a mission to Belgrade and to the
Kosovo capital Pristina to see how to set up reception centers for
the refugees as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Dini also reiterated the need to continue pressing Yugoslav and
Kosovo leaders to start "serious and constructive" negotiations on
the future status of autonomy that will enable Kosovo residents to
govern themselves.
</P>
<P>
This status should be modeled on the proposal made by U.S.
Ambassador to Macedonia Christopher Hill, with the support of the
Contact Group, Dini said.
</P>
<P>
That proposal envisages a Kosovo parliament and government but
falls short of independence which Kosovo is still demanding.
</P>
<P>
Italy and others have been pressing for a compromise in which
Kosovo becomes a third repubic in the Yugoslav federation, on a
par with Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo elections are supposed to take place within a year, with
the OSCE team verifying their correctness.
</P>
<P>
Signing the verification deal in Belgrade Friday, OSCE duty
chief Bronislaw Geremek said it opened a "possibility" for peace
but was just the "first step."
</P>
<P>
OSCE Thursday approved the plan to send the verification
mission to the troubled Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
The team of observers will verify Yugoslavia's compliance with
the United Nations Security Council Resolution 1199, which calls
for an immediate ceasefire, a withdrawal of Serb forces from
Kosovo, the return of refugees, and the start of autonomy talks
with ethnic Albanians there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
