<HEADLINE> Central China Province Hosts Fair on Economic, Tech Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 7,000 businessmen
from home and abroad gather here today to attend the fair of
foreign economic and technological cooperation in central and
western parts of China.
</P>
<P>
The today-opened fair, co-sponsored by the Office of Overseas
Chinese Affairs of the State Council and Hunan Provincial
Government, is aimed at promoting the opening up of central and
western regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
The four-day fair puts forward over 1,000 programs seeking
cooperation covering 11 industries such as energy resources,
communications, telecommunications, machinery, building materials,
power, chemistry, electronics, agriculture and processing
industry, as well as forestry, food-processing and medicines.
</P>
<P>
Guo Dongpo, director of the Office of Overseas Chinese Affairs,
said that the Chinese government has attached great importance to
the development of central and western parts of the country since
the beginning of the 1990s. China has worked out and will adopt a
series of polices encouraging investment in these regions.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the current fair will provide a chance for
international economic circles and enterpreneurs to have a better
understanding of China's central and western parts, and will play
its role as a bridge linking the central and western regions with
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
At today's opening ceremony, Li Rongrong, vice-minister of the
State Development Planning Commission, Chen Bangzhu, vice-minister
of the State Economic and Trade Commission and Sun Guangxiang,
vice-minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, explained
respectively China's policies and plans on reform of the
investment system, the technological up-grading and reform of
state-owned enterprises, and policies on introduction of foreign
funds.  
