<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Export Target for This Year Still Within </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Finance Ministry is
confident that Thailand's overall export target for this year of
60 billion U.S. dollars will be achieved, the Bangkok Post
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This year's export target is 3 percent higher than the 58.37
billion U.S. dollars achieved last year.
</P>
<P>
Charnchai Musignisarkorn, deputy director-general of the Fiscal
Policy Office, was quoted as saying that exports would pick up in
the last three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Investment in manufacturing had risen while the economic
outlook in foreign markets had also improved, Charnchai noted.
</P>
<P>
According to customs figures, Thailand's exports in September
were 4.68 billion U.S. dollars, down by 9.2 percent from the same
month last year but up by 7.6 percent from August.
</P>
<P>
For the nine months to September, the country's exports reached
40.65 billion U.S. dollars, down by 5.9 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
The baht value of exports continued to rise steadily. In
September the figure was 190.6 billion baht, up by 5.3 percent
from the same month last year and up by 6.9 percent from August.
</P>
<P>
Exports in baht terms for the first nine months of the year
were 1,740 billion baht, up by 44 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports in September were valued at 3.37 billion U.S. dollars,
down by 3 percent from the same month last year and down by 0.03
percent from August. Imports for the nine months to September were
31.87 billion U.S. dollars, down by 36.5 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's trade surplus in September was 1.31 billion U.S.
dollars, the highest in the past nine months. The surplus for the
year to date was 8.78 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"it is possible that September will be starting point for the
economic recovery. If exports over the next three months improve
as expected, we are certain that our economy has reached its
lowest point and will gradually improve next year," Charnchai
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
