<HEADLINE> D'Alema Asked to Lead Italy's New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro Friday asked Massimo D'Alema, the leader of the Left
Democrats, to try to form a new governing majority.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema, who leads the largest party in the center-left Olive
Tree alliance, accepted the mandate Friday evening after a
30-minute meeting with Scalfaro.
</P>
<P>
If D'Alema succeeds, he will become the first former Communist
to head a government in Italy.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema told reporters after the meeting that he would proceed
with "great caution" in his attempt to form a "strong and stable"
government.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was "necessary to listen with great care" to
political forces in order to ascertain "the effective existence of
the majority required for a stable government."
</P>
<P>
During Scalfaro's round of political consultations on Thursday
and Friday, party leaders had shown a certain receptiveness to the
idea of his mandate, said D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
And the reactions of moderate Marxists and the centrist
Democratic Union for the Republic (UDR) had so far given him hope
of being able to draw together a majority, he added.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema vowed to resume the cause of constitutional reform,
especially electoral reform, which is vital for creating a more
stable system of government.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema, 49, also expressed his gratitude to Romano Prodi,
whose attempt to revive his government failed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's government fell after it lost the support of the
hard-line Communist Refoundation party over the 1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema also appealed to Communist Refoundation leader Fausto
Bertinotti to relent over the budget, saying the budget was a
"good one." 
</P>
