<HEADLINE> Mysterious Underground Chamber to Come to Light </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists are to open the
door of a newly-discovered underground chamber under an ancient
Chinese tower at 12:00 today,
</P>
<P>
The chamber was discovered beneath the 1,400-year-old Fawang
Tower in the southern part of Zhouzhi County in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province, a place 70-80 kilometers away from the
provincial capital of Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
After locating the door of the chamber on October 7,
archeologists and technicians worked hard, removing a huge heap of
rubble blocking it.
</P>
<P>
The 30-meter-high Fawang Tower was built in 601 by Yang Jian,
an emperor of the Sui Dynasty (581-618). It is believed to be the
oldest tower ever preserved in China, and the only tower left
built in the Sui Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
In order to make way for a local water project, the local
government decided to move the tower and the Xianyou Temple where
the tower is located. With the approval of the State Council, the
task began in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
An 11.9 cm-long, 7.6 cm-wide, 10.5 cm-high bronze coffin,
containing two bean-sized sariras -- a combination of bone ashes
of eminent Buddhist monks -- had already been found while working
on the second floor of the tower.
</P>
<P>
Today's excavation will be broadcast live by the China Central
Television (CCTV), the first time the CCTV live broadcasts
excavation process of an archeological finding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministry Emphasizes Rural Legal Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Justice
yesterday called on its subordinate organs to provide high-quality
services for farmers, the "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry circular said local law firms, public notary
offices and other legal service organizations should pay attention
to the needs of the countryside.
</P>
<P>
The circular was issued shortly after the Third Plenary Session
of the 15th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) early this week. The session highlighted the importance of
agriculture and rural work in China.
</P>
<P>
The circular said legal service organs should actively
participate in economic development in rural areas by helping with
extensions of terms for contracted land, by protecting the lawful
rights of township enterprises and by guiding farmers in
establishing various shareholding firms as well as assisting the
work of collective entities.
</P>
<P>
Local legal service providers are required to reduce the
burdens of farmers in keeping with related laws and protect
farmers from fake and poor-quality grain seed, fertilizers and
farm chemicals.
</P>
<P>
They should also play an important role in the establishment of
an open, uniform, competitive and orderly agricultural
market. These organs must take the initiative to aid local
organizations in the popularization of agricultural techniques by
drafting related popularization contracts and by strengthening the
protection of intellectual property rights covering such
techniques.
</P>
<P>
The circular emphasized that legal education in the
countryside, especially about the laws that have a direct impact
on rural life, such as the Law of Agriculture, the Anti-flood Law
and the Land Administration Law should be provided.
</P>
<P>
Among China's more than 1.2 billion people, some 900 million
are farmers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
