<HEADLINE> Thailand to pressure EU to Use New Figures for trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ministry spokesman Kobsak Chutikul said Friday that the
European Commission (EC) stand would affect three items in
agricultural sector -- vegetables and fruits, fishery and food as
well as beverages -- which constitute 90 percent of Thai exports
to the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The EU took the stand after a review of its Generalized System
of Preferences last month.
</P>
<P>
Thailand had called on the EC, which is the external trade arm
of the European Union, to use 1997 growth figures which reflect
Thailand's economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
But the EU Council of Ministers is yet to endorse the EC
review and Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan will try to lobby
for their support. Surin will invite the ambassadors in Bangkok of
the EU troika -- Britain, Austria and Germany -- to a meeting
soon, Kobsak was quoted Saturday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
