<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia, OSCE Sign Accord on Verification Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia Friday signed the
agreement on a verification mission in Kosovo with the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Yugoslavia will allow 2,000 unarmed
observers from the 54-nation OSCE into Kosovo to verify its
compliance with U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Yugoslav Minister of Foreign Affairs
Zivadin Jovanovic and the current OSCE Chairman and Polish Foreign
Minister Bronislaw Geremek
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has been asked by the United Nations and the
six-nation Contact Group for the former Yugoslavia to withdraw its
army and special police forces from the Kosovo province, which had
been fighting with the splittist ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The accord was reached by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke in Belgrade on October 13.
</P>
<P>
The Yogoslav Foreign Ministry pointed out in a statement that
the accord embodied Yugoslavia's policy on a peaceful solution to
the problems in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It said that Yugoslavia hopes the OSCE mission would report
the real situation in Kosovo to the international community.
</P>
<P>
Later, Geremek traveled to the Kosovo capital of Pristina and
briefed ethnic Albanian political leader in Kosovo Ibrahim Rugova
on the signing of the accord.
</P>
<P>
Rugova told Geremek that ethnic Albanians in Kosovo will take a
friendly attitude to the OSCE verification mission.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, in a letter to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic on Friday, said that the United
Nations will send a high-level delegation to Kosovo to have an
on-the-spot study on the situation.
</P>
<P>
Annan congratulated Milosevic over the agreement he reached
with Holbrooke on a peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis, hoping
that the agreement will mark "a turning point" in ending the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, NATO on Friday extended its ultimatum for air
strikes in Kosovo to October 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
