<HEADLINE> Venezuela Industrial Sector Cuts 47,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The Venezuelan industrial
sector cut 47,000 jobs from January to September of this year, as
a result of the economic recession the country is undergoing.
</P>
<P>
About 19,000 persons lost their jobs between July and
September, a 5.8 percent increase in unemployment, said a poll of
the industrial sector by the "Datanalisis" Firm.
</P>
<P>
Luis Henrique Ball, Venezuelan Industrialists Confederation
president, said the industrial sector was hit by a rise in the
interest rates and budget cuts, which although positive, have
produced a recessive effect.
</P>
<P>
The economic depression was also attributed to production
cutbacks. In that sense, 60 percent of the 380 firms polled said
their production volume declined in comparison with the same
quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The drop in domestic demands, inflation, political uncertainty,
unfair competition and the rise in raw material costs are among
the factors that hit the sector during this quarter, said the
poll. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Europe Associations Oppose Superleague </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Central and East European
football associations here on Friday voiced their strong protests
against the proposed breakaway superleague for the continent.
</P>
<P>
At a summit here attended by a number of senior UEFA officials
as well as soccer leaders from the region, the regional soccer
chiefs also expressed "total support for the position of UEFA".
</P>
<P>
Attila Kovacs, president of the Hungarian Football Federation
who are hosting the conference, spoke on behalf of his counterpa
rts that the superleague would see the rich get richer and the
poor get poorer while in the Champions' League everyone has a
chance to be involved.
</P>
<P>
UEFA president Lennart Johansson said the meeting of 23
football associations from the region had unanimously backed
UEFA's opposition to the superleague and supported UEFA's
expanded Champions' League.
</P>
<P>
Only two clubs from the region -- Yugoslavia's Crvena Zvezda
and Russia's Spartak Moscow -- are known to have been involved in
talks with Milan-based superleague backers Media Partners.
</P>
<P>
They have been warned by their national football associations
to expect no support if they joined the superleague. 
</P>
</TEXT>
