<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 17 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of China's
National People's Congress (NPC), said at the 6th General Assembly
of the Asia-Pacific Parliamentarians Conference on Environment and
Development in Guilin yesterday, that China will continue to
enhance environment protection.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the Third Plenary Session of the 15th Central
Committee of the CPC held recently in Beijing decided to increase
water conservation construction and to accelerate the control of
large rivers and lakes like the Yangtze and Yellow rivers and
Taihu Lake to improve China's environment and its capacity to
resist natural calamities.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing has called on society to lend a
helping hand to some 60 million disabled persons to allow them to
enjoy equal dignity and the same rights as ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
Li told the opening ceremony of the Third National Congress of
the China Disabled Persons' Federation yesterday in Beijing that
helping the disabled is an important symbol of civilization and
social progress.
</P>
<P>
China has greatly improved the livelihoods of the disabled over
the past decade, with 4.16 million disabled people having
benefited from nationwide rehabilitation programs that have helped
2.1 million cataract sufferers see again and 90,000 deaf-mute
children speak, in addition to other achievements in helping the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The paper frontpaged the full text of a speech by Jiang
Zemin on the study of Deng Xiaoping Theory.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a work meeting on July 17, 1998, Jiang, general
secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), called on the entire Party to further study Deng Xiaoping
Theory and carry it out in line with the guideline of the 15th CPC
National Congress.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that by this study, officials at various
levels will make new progress in understanding Deng Xiaoping
Theory and the guideline of the 15th CPC National Congress, and
push forward reform and construction.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's economy grew 7.2 percent in the first three quarters
of the year on a year-on-year basis, the State Statistics Bureau
(SSB) said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The result fell short of the full-year target of 8 percent, but
SSB spokesman Ye Zhen said an anticipated surge in economic growth
in the last quarter will make the goal achievable.
</P>
<P>
-- Koo Chen-fu, chairman of the Taiwan-based Straits Exchange
Foundation (SEF), arrived in Beijing yesterday from Shanghai to
continue a six-day tour on the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Koo, 81, reached a four-point consensus with Wang Daohan, 83,
chairman of the Beijing-based Association for Relations Across the
Taiwan Strait (ARATS), on Thursday in Shanghai in their second
meeting. 
