<HEADLINE> Brazil to Float Multi-Billion-Dollar New Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAO PAULO, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Brazil is planning to float
bonds worth of five billion U.S. dollars to beef up the central
bank's reserves, the National Development Bank of Brazil announced
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bonds would be backed by the money produced by income from
privatization or state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, budget cuts could facilitate a financial rescue
package put together by the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
which the Brazilian financial circles expected to amount to some
30 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of this package is to help Brazil to defend its
currency against devaluation. The cruzeiro real is already
subjected to big speculative pressures in the market.
</P>
<P>
Under Brazilian law, the U.S. dollars obtained from the sale of
bonds must be deposited in the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian international reserves had dropped from 67 billion
U.S. dollars to only 45 billion in recent two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
