<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mosquito Vector of Dengue Discovered in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, October 16 (Xinhua) -- A mosquito species, much
stronger than the species known today, has been identified by the
Costa Rican health authorities as one transmitting the endemic
diseases of dengue fever and malaria in the region.
</P>
<P>
Health authorities found larvae of "Aedes albopictus" in three
homes in the region of La Virgen de Sarapiqui in the Atlantic zone
of the country, Health Minister Rogelio Pardo told the local media
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The combat against this species, said Pardo, is more difficult,
because it not only lives in houses, but also survives easily in
forests. It adapts to almost any environment and it is therefore
more difficult to combat.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry has launched an intense campaign against
the mosquito species, instructing local residents to eliminate
water deposits in houses, yards and streets where the mosquito
lays eggs and where its larvae develops.
</P>
<P>
Dengue is a disease transmitted by the mosquito, that causes
high fever, headaches and body aches, and can be fetal if there is
a relapse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
