<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA Chief: "Take it or leave it" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- European soccer governing body
UEFA president Lennart Johansson said in Budapest on Friday his
European soccer governing body was committed to its new-look
Champions' League and the continent's major clubs could "take it
or leave it".
</P>
<P>
According to local reports on Friday, Johansson said UEFA was
willing to involve the elite clubs in talks but decisions
remained with the national football associations.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to a statement on Wednesday by 12 of Europe's top
clubs seeking a greater role in the organisation and financial
affairs of the Champions' League, Johansson said: "all of a
sudden every club must have a say about everything. Sometimes it
is 16 clubs, then 12 clubs and then three clubs."
</P>
<P>
"They would like to be involved. I think they should be
involved and we will talk to them and we will explain what we can
do. But we have our concept and they have to take it or leave
it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he believed that UEFA's reformed European competition
structure would satisfy the financial demands of clubs
threatening to form a breakaway superleague, Johansson said that
decision would be taken by each member country not the elite
clubs.
</P>
<P>
"We are satisfied (with the reforms) and the majority of
countries in Europe are satisfied. They will take a decision on
November 24. They will confirm to us that this is the way to go.
We cannot be guided by 10 or 12 or 16 clubs, there are 26 million
football players in Europe and there are 51 countries."
</P>
<P>
But Johansson, in Budapest for a meeting with leaders of 22
central and east European football associations, said UEFA would
be willing to involve the big clubs more closely in decision
making.
</P>
<P>
"Being the ones who contribute so much financially, helping us
to show solidarity to all of Europe, if they want to be involved
and work together why not? This is the democratic way of working
which I fully accept."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, 12 of Europe's top clubs met in Milan to discuss
the latest developments in the superleague saga and issued a
joint statement through AC Milan.
</P>
<P>
The meeting followed a UEFA announcement last week of reforms
to the European Champions' League, expanding the competition from
24 to 32 clubs next season when the UEFA and Cup Winners' Cups
will be merged.
</P>
<P>
The changes came in response to attempts by Milan-based Media
Partners to set up a 1.2 billion U.S. dollars superleague.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
