drug-resistant strains in patient's semen and blood, researchers
from U.S. and Switzerland reported in the latest issue of the AIDS
journal.
</P>
<P>
The researchers studied 11 HIV-infected men in North Carolina
and Switzerland. Some of those who were treated prior to the study
had AIDS strains that had mutated and developed resistance to
antiviral drugs. Most of the volunteers with these resistant
viruses had different viral strains in their semen and blood.
(US-AIDS Virus-Mutation)
</P>
