<HEADLINE> "Indonesia Spectacular" Program Launched to Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 17 (Xinhua) -- An ambitious program dubbed as
the "Indonesia Spectacular" was launched by President B.J. Habibie
in a ceremony at the State Palace here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The five-month long program aims to restore the image of
Indonesia as a tourist destination, as well as to attract more
foreign tourists to come to the country.
</P>
<P>
Habibie stressed in his speech that violent mass riots and
lootings were things of the past.
</P>
<P>
"Our country is extensive. Not all regions in the country are
hit by riots and disturbances and such information should be
disseminated abroad," the president was quoted by national
newspapers Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Habibie welcomed the presence of foreign tour operators and
travel writers.
</P>
<P>
"Their presence here will enable them to witness the
development of the country. They can converse with the people and
go to tourist destinations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the current economic difficulties faced by
businessmen, the president called on them to turn their attention
to the tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
The program was initiated by the Association of Indonesian
Travel Agencies (ASITA) in close cooperation with the national
flag carrier Garuda and 30 foreign airlines. It will also involve
400 tour operators and travel writers from across the globe.
</P>
<P>
ASITA's action plan includes an invitation to tour operators
and travel writers from around the world to travel to all corners
of the archipelago free of air charge to see, by themselves, the
beauty and safety of the country, ASITA Chairman Muljono
Herlambang said.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister of Tourism, Arts and Culture Marzuki
Usman, the program was part of the "Let's Go Indonesia" campaign
launched sometime ago.
</P>
<P>
Tourism was Indonesia's third largest foreign exchange earner
last year after the oil and gas as well as textile and garments
sectors, bringing in 6.6 billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier projected overseas tourist arrivals this
year to total between 5.6 million and 6.5 million, but the
country's calamities have forced the target to be revised to 4.6
million, or a 10 percent decline from 5.1 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government had expressed hopes tourism could become the
country's largest foreign exchange earner in 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
