<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India Open Talks on Kashmir Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and India will take
up the contentious Kashmir issue on Saturday for an exclusive
discussion for the first time in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad and his Indian
counterpart K. Ragunath will devote the second day of their
on-going talks to the Kashmir dispute which has been a flash-point
between the two countries since their independence.
</P>
<P>
Sovereignty over the Kashmir, about twice the size of Virginia,
was left unresolved when the Indian Subcontinent was divided into
India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The two South Asian neighbors have already fought three wars,
two of which were over Kashmir, in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
And the territorial dispute over the Himalayan state has
rendered all the reconciliation efforts by Islamabad and New Delhi
fruitless because of the two sides' seemingly uncompromising
positions.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan insists that the core issue of Kashmir should be
resolved before any other agreements can be reached while India
favors first taking up commercial and trade issues, saying the
status of Kashmir is not negotiable. 
</P>
