<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's SPD, Greens Agree on Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 16 (Xinhua) -- Chancellor-elect Gerhard
Schroeder's Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the Greens party
have apparently cleared a major hurdle in forming a center-left
coalition government in Bonn after agreeing on a common foreign
policy program on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a new round of coalition talks with the Greens on
Friday, Guenter Verheugen, a SPD expert of foreign affairs, said
that the SPD-Greens program would guarantee continuity and
reliability of German foreign and security policy.
</P>
<P>
As a major policy shift, Greens officials indicated on Friday
that the future German government would not make it a priority to
press for a permanent seat for Germany in the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Instead Bonn would try first to seek "a European solution",
said Ludger Volmer, the Greens expert on foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Eager to enter government for the first time since its founding
in 1979, the Greens has apparently refrained from asserting its
radical foreign policy demands like a call for an unilateral
German withdrawal from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO).
</P>
<P>
Negotiators of the two parties said that a SPD-Greens
government would not rule out Germany's participation in
international peacekeeping missions in the future provided that
such moves are approved by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The pacifist Greens has so far categorically rejected any
deployment of German troops abroad.
</P>
<P>
The SPD and Greens on Friday also agreed to seek a strengthened
role for the United Nations and the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in preventing and solving regional
conflicts like the recent one in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
They also pledged that Germany would spend more on development
aid for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The SPD-Greens foreign policy program still views the NATO as
indispensable for peace in Europe. It also says that the United
States will remain the most important partner for Germany outside
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The SPD and Greens are planning to wind up their coalition
talks by Monday. If a comprehensive deal could be reached, the new
government is expected to be sworn in by the end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
