<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Build New Generation of Military Rockets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Department of
Defense on Friday announced that it will build the nation's next
generation of military rockets that will also help put satellites
in space at lower cost.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force on Friday awarded contracts worth 3.03
billion U.S. dollars to Boeing Co. and Lockheed Martin Corp. to
carry out the program, the Pentagon said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Boeing, which assembles launchers in
Huntington Beach, Calif., will conduct 19 launches and Lockheed
Martin, whose main rocket plant is in Denver, will have nine, the
Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The program is dubbed the Evolved Expendable Launch Vehicle,
and it will replace the nation's current fleet of medium- and
heavy-lift military launch systems, the Delta, Atlas and Titan,
with two modular families of launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The modular systems will be used in different combinations to
carry satellites into orbit at less cost than current launchers.
They will also be used in missions for the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration and commercial users, as well as the
military, the Associated Press said, citing military officials.
</P>
<P>
The program was also designed to maintain competition in the
space launch arena, reduce risk and provide assured access to
space for government and commercial payloads, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The new systems would save five billion dollars to 10 billion
dollars over the life of the program.
</P>
<P>
The government payloads -- about a half-dozen of them
classified and presumably spy satellites -- will be put in space
between fiscal 2002 and 2006. The other launches involved global
positioning and communication satellites among others, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
During 1999 to 2002, the two companies will complete the
development of their launch vehicles, and construct and activate
the launch sites at Cape Canaveral Air Station, Florida, and
Vandenberg Air Force Base, California. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981017.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Accuses Republicans of Partisanship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Friday accused Republicans of "pure old-fashioned partisanship"
in killing everything from anti-smoking legislation to health-care
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also expressed concern about a low voter turnout in
mid-term elections. The election will be decided not only by which
side has the better argument but also "who shows up," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
A day after reaching a budget deal with Republicans, the
president staged a White House rally with three dozen members of
Congress and then flew to Chicago to campaign for Carol
Moseley-Braun, the first black woman elected to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Mosely-Braun made a passing reference to the impeachment threat
hanging over Clinton when she said Republicans "should leave this
man alone and let him do his job." The audience applauded loudly,
the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, both at the White House and in Chicago, said Congress,
in its rush to leave town, had accomplished major achievements
with legislation to hire 100,000 new teachers, help farmers,
protect the environment and reserve budget surpluses for Social
Security remedies rather than election-year tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that in "eight months of partisanship, too
many dreams of too many families were deferred." He said that
"partisanship killed" the patients' bill of rights for Health
Maintenance Organization (HMO) reforms and legislation to build or
modernize schools, to increase the minimum wage and to overhaul
campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
And he said that "partisanship killed the comprehensive
anti-tobacco legislation which would have saved millions of young
Americans from painful and premature death.... This was about
whether we were going to take appropriate action to save our
children, and pure, old-fashioned partisanship killed it."
</P>
<P>
Republicans responded to Clinton's criticism. House Ways and
Means Committee chairman Bill Archer said, "President Clinton
should stop pretending he saved the surplus for Social Security.
The president compounds his credibility problem with this Congress
and the American people when he says he hasn't spent the surplus."
</P>
</TEXT>
