<HEADLINE> U.S.: Milosevic Not Complies Fully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Friday that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has not yet
fully complied with the U.N. demands and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) should remain ready to act.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin made the remarks at a
regular briefing in response to questions on NATO's decision to
postpone its activation order, which expires on Saturday, for
another ten days.
</P>
<P>
"Our view of the decision they should make is that there has
not yet been full compliance by Milosevic with the requirements of
the international community, and therefore, we believe NATO's gun
should remain cocked," said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
"The exact nature of that extension I think will be up to NATO
authorities to describe, but generically speaking, what we're
talking about is continuing to provide General (Willy) Clark the
authority to use force by a later date now, to extend the time
frame, if there is not compliance by President Milosevic," he
added.
</P>
<P>
However, Rubin said that reports have indicated that Milosevic
is complying with NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
"There are reports, reliable reports from our monitors, that a
significant number of internally displaced persons, the people up
in the hills, are returning to their homes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Rubin also admitted that Yugoslav military forces
and police units are "no longer in the field."
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslav military forces and police units -- our assessment is
that about half of those that were in Kosovo are no longer in the
field, which means either they're in barracks or they're out of
Kosovo," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"There are significant signs of police units having moved, and
clearly, as I indicated, the police presence is diminished," he added.
</P>
<P>
Monitors have reported that a Yugoslav military armored brigade
departed from its location where it was deployed just a month ago,
according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, a military police has also departed its recent
location.  
</P>
</TEXT>
